1
00:01:23,208 --> 00:01:24,125
I call it a hit.

2
00:01:24,334 --> 00:01:26,169
- What'll your review say?
VALET: Car, sir?

3
00:01:26,378 --> 00:01:29,005
I like it too,
so I guess I'll pan it.

4
00:01:29,214 --> 00:01:30,173
That's logical.

5
00:01:30,382 --> 00:01:33,634
My publisher resents Cohan impersonating
the president of the United States.

6
00:01:33,844 --> 00:01:36,429
Says our young readers dream
of being president.

7
00:01:36,638 --> 00:01:38,473
"I'd rather be right than be president."

8
00:01:38,682 --> 00:01:41,392
Cohan may find out he isn't either one.

9
00:01:41,602 --> 00:01:43,186
[BOTH LAUGH]

10
00:01:45,731 --> 00:01:47,273
I don't see how George does it
at his age.

11
00:01:47,483 --> 00:01:49,567
I remember him
when he was a little boy.

12
00:01:49,777 --> 00:01:52,528
MAN: Congratulations, George, old boy.
You did a great job.

13
00:01:52,738 --> 00:01:54,614
- Thanks. Thanks very much.
WOMAN: Congratulations.

14
00:01:54,823 --> 00:01:58,034
- You had him down to a tee.
- We're still treading on dangerous ground.

15
00:01:58,243 --> 00:02:00,953
Imitating the president,
a lot of people aren't gonna like it.

16
00:02:01,163 --> 00:02:03,414
It's all good, clean fun.
Didn't they enjoy it in Boston?

17
00:02:03,624 --> 00:02:05,750
- Never could do anything wrong in Boston.
- Ha-ha-ha!

18
00:02:05,959 --> 00:02:08,377
Greatest man in the United States
played by the greatest actor.

19
00:02:08,587 --> 00:02:11,923
Nothing wrong with that, especially
when the greatest actor is my husband.

20
00:02:12,132 --> 00:02:13,549
- This could be treason.
- Don't worry.

21
00:02:13,759 --> 00:02:15,843
I know a dollar-a-year man
who'll take care of you.

22
00:02:16,053 --> 00:02:18,221
- A lot would like to shoot actors.
- Save these telegrams.

23
00:02:18,430 --> 00:02:19,722
The government needs paper.

24
00:02:19,932 --> 00:02:22,725
You've got a list like who's who here.
There's everybody but Hirohito.

25
00:02:22,935 --> 00:02:24,936
- We'll bring him in on a shutter.
- Here's mine.

26
00:02:25,145 --> 00:02:27,939
- Won't you read all that cleverness?
- What makes you think I didn't?

27
00:02:28,148 --> 00:02:31,442
I didn't know there was that much love left
in the entire Western Union codebook.

28
00:02:31,652 --> 00:02:33,611
PHOTOGRAPHER: Hold that. Thank you.
SAM: Uh-oh.

29
00:02:33,821 --> 00:02:36,823
- Don't bother me.
- It's from the White House.

30
00:02:37,032 --> 00:02:38,533
- That bothers me.
- Here.

31
00:02:38,742 --> 00:02:41,244
You read it, Sam. These aren't
my reading glasses. What's it say?

32
00:02:41,453 --> 00:02:43,621
"George M. Cohan,
the Alvin Theater, New York.

33
00:02:43,831 --> 00:02:46,124
The president of the U.S. requests
that you call upon him...

34
00:02:46,333 --> 00:02:49,502
...at your earliest convenience
in regard to a personal matter.

35
00:02:49,711 --> 00:02:52,797
Kindly reply for definite appointment
at White House.

36
00:02:53,006 --> 00:02:55,633
Steven T. Early,
secretary to the president."

37
00:02:55,843 --> 00:02:57,426
GEORGE:
Hmm.

38
00:02:57,636 --> 00:02:59,345
There you are, Sam.

39
00:02:59,555 --> 00:03:01,139
There you are. What did I tell you?

40
00:03:01,348 --> 00:03:03,933
Coming at a time like this,
with everything he has on his mind...

41
00:03:04,143 --> 00:03:05,935
...this is not just a casual invitation.

42
00:03:06,145 --> 00:03:07,228
This is important.

43
00:03:07,437 --> 00:03:09,105
- I think we're in trouble.
- Don't worry.

44
00:03:09,314 --> 00:03:11,566
They don't telegraph you to come
and be shot at sunrise.

45
00:03:11,775 --> 00:03:12,900
He doesn't get up that early.

46
00:03:13,110 --> 00:03:18,156
Besides, I've got a run-of-the-play contract.
Fine time to make lame jokes. Hmm.

47
00:03:18,365 --> 00:03:21,826
I'm worried, Sam. I'm really worried.

48
00:03:38,260 --> 00:03:39,510
GUARD:
Halt!

49
00:03:42,806 --> 00:03:45,308
- Yes, sir. What can I do for you?
- I've got an appointment.

50
00:03:45,517 --> 00:03:47,935
- And the name, please?
- Cohan. George M. Cohan.

51
00:03:48,145 --> 00:03:51,063
All right, sir, if you'll wait just one moment,
I'll call.

52
00:03:55,235 --> 00:03:58,446
Sergeant Lewis
at the Pennsylvania Avenue gate.

53
00:03:59,907 --> 00:04:02,533
- Good evening, Mr. Cohan.
- Good evening.

54
00:04:02,743 --> 00:04:05,536
- We've been expecting you.
- Thank you.

55
00:04:08,916 --> 00:04:12,001
Why, your coat's wet.
Didn't you come in the car?

56
00:04:12,211 --> 00:04:13,836
No, I walked up from the station.

57
00:04:14,046 --> 00:04:16,797
Washington's a great town to walk in.
I always get a kick out of it.

58
00:04:17,007 --> 00:04:19,675
Yes, indeed.
Won't you come with me?

59
00:04:22,429 --> 00:04:25,181
I was supposed to be off-duty
this evening, Mr. Cohan...

60
00:04:25,390 --> 00:04:27,266
...but when I heard you was coming,
I thought...

61
00:04:27,476 --> 00:04:29,227
...I would like to see
if you looked the same.

62
00:04:29,436 --> 00:04:31,187
That depends just
on when you saw me last.

63
00:04:31,396 --> 00:04:34,023
Well, it must have been
30-some years ago.

64
00:04:34,233 --> 00:04:36,734
I was valet for Mr. Teddy Roosevelt.

65
00:04:36,944 --> 00:04:39,070
He got me a seat up in the gallery.

66
00:04:39,279 --> 00:04:41,239
The play was George Washington, Jr.

67
00:04:41,448 --> 00:04:45,576
And you was just singing and dancing
all about the grand old flag.

68
00:04:45,786 --> 00:04:48,788
Mr. Teddy used to sing it in his bathtub.

69
00:04:48,997 --> 00:04:51,123
- It was a good old song in its day.
- Yes, sir, it was...

70
00:04:51,333 --> 00:04:54,710
...and it's just as good today
as it ever was.

71
00:04:57,923 --> 00:04:58,881
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

72
00:04:59,091 --> 00:05:00,591
PRESIDENT:
Come in.

73
00:05:05,097 --> 00:05:06,639
Well, hello there.

74
00:05:06,848 --> 00:05:09,308
- How's my double?
- Your double isn't any too sure.

75
00:05:09,559 --> 00:05:10,768
Give me time
to work on that one.

76
00:05:10,978 --> 00:05:13,938
Why, I was told you knew
all the answers.

77
00:05:14,147 --> 00:05:16,816
There was a time when I thought so.
Right now, I wish I did.

78
00:05:17,025 --> 00:05:20,361
Yes, so do I.
Sit down, Mr. Cohan.

79
00:05:20,570 --> 00:05:21,821
Thanks.

80
00:05:22,030 --> 00:05:24,198
- You know, I'm a little bit nervous.
- Heh-heh-heh.

81
00:05:24,408 --> 00:05:26,951
I'm sorry I missed the opening
of your show.

82
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:28,327
Maybe just as well.

83
00:05:28,537 --> 00:05:32,290
Don't worry about it.
We understand each other perfectly.

84
00:05:32,499 --> 00:05:34,917
- I think so.
- The Herald Tribune says...

85
00:05:35,127 --> 00:05:38,671
...that you make a better president
and I'd rather be right than I am.

86
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:40,756
Don't forget,
that's a Republican newspaper.

87
00:05:40,966 --> 00:05:42,133
[PRESIDENT CHUCKLES]

88
00:05:42,342 --> 00:05:46,637
I can remember you and your family
very well. The Four Cohans.

89
00:05:46,847 --> 00:05:49,056
Do you, really, Mr. President?
That's a long time ago.

90
00:05:49,266 --> 00:05:53,144
Yes. It was while I was attending school
near Boston.

91
00:05:53,353 --> 00:05:54,729
I was a pretty cocky kid those days.

92
00:05:54,938 --> 00:05:57,398
Pretty cocky kid.
A regular Yankee Doodle Dandy.

93
00:05:57,607 --> 00:05:59,567
Always carrying a flag
in a parade or following one.

94
00:05:59,776 --> 00:06:02,653
- I hope you haven't outgrown the habit.
- Not a chance.

95
00:06:02,863 --> 00:06:07,074
That's one thing I always admired
about you Irish-Americans.

96
00:06:07,284 --> 00:06:10,745
You carry your love of country like a flag,
right out in the open.

97
00:06:10,954 --> 00:06:12,121
It's a great quality.

98
00:06:12,331 --> 00:06:15,124
I inherited that,
got that from my father.

99
00:06:15,334 --> 00:06:17,585
He ran away to the Civil War
when he was 13.

100
00:06:17,794 --> 00:06:19,545
Proudest kid in the state
of Massachusetts.

101
00:06:19,755 --> 00:06:23,257
So you've spent your life
telling the other 47 states...

102
00:06:23,467 --> 00:06:25,051
...what a great country it is.

103
00:06:25,260 --> 00:06:27,011
I never thought of it
just that way before...

104
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:28,846
...but I guess
that's about the size of it.

105
00:06:29,056 --> 00:06:30,681
And I lost no time, either.

106
00:06:30,891 --> 00:06:33,976
It started with a very funny incident,
about 60 years ago.

107
00:06:34,186 --> 00:06:36,520
It was in Providence, Rhode Island,
on the Fourth of July.

108
00:06:36,730 --> 00:06:39,190
There weren't so many stars then,
in the flag or on the stage...

109
00:06:39,399 --> 00:06:41,442
...but folks knew that more were coming.

110
00:06:41,651 --> 00:06:44,653
They were optimistic, happy and expectant.

111
00:06:44,863 --> 00:06:47,198
The beginning of the Horatio Alger Age.

112
00:06:47,407 --> 00:06:50,368
[MARCHING BAND PLAYING
AND CROWD CHEERING]

113
00:07:01,797 --> 00:07:04,048
My father was playing in a variety,
breaking in a single.

114
00:07:04,257 --> 00:07:05,883
Nobody was more expectant
than he was...

115
00:07:06,093 --> 00:07:07,551
...unless it was my mother.

116
00:07:07,761 --> 00:07:09,678
She was busy right then
on a smaller production.

117
00:07:09,888 --> 00:07:11,347
[SINGING]
Larry O'Leary is me name

118
00:07:11,556 --> 00:07:13,349
By trade I am a dancing master

119
00:07:13,558 --> 00:07:15,476
There's no one can teach the same

120
00:07:15,685 --> 00:07:19,980
Nor teach it any faster

121
00:07:20,190 --> 00:07:22,817
It's easy, very easy

122
00:07:23,026 --> 00:07:25,778
If you watch every twist, every turn

123
00:07:25,987 --> 00:07:28,823
Keep your eyes upon me
And surprised you will be

124
00:07:29,032 --> 00:07:32,159
At the dancing you have yet to learn

125
00:07:32,369 --> 00:07:34,328
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING MERRY MUSIC]

126
00:07:43,505 --> 00:07:46,257
Keep your eyes upon me
And surprised you will be

127
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:48,717
At the dancing you have yet to learn

128
00:07:48,927 --> 00:07:50,553
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

129
00:07:50,762 --> 00:07:52,096
- Any messages come for me?
- Not yet.

130
00:07:52,305 --> 00:07:54,223
- Better take a bow, Jerry.
- Can't. I gotta leave.

131
00:07:54,433 --> 00:07:56,267
MAX: Watch that water!
- Max, I gotta leave.

132
00:07:56,476 --> 00:07:59,103
- I gotta find out what's happening.
- Oh, for heaven's sake, Jerry.

133
00:07:59,312 --> 00:08:01,897
Take up Number 3.
You're on. Go ahead. Light's up.

134
00:08:02,107 --> 00:08:03,190
- Bye, Sally.
- Good luck.

135
00:08:03,400 --> 00:08:05,276
You can't run through the streets
in that outfit.

136
00:08:05,485 --> 00:08:07,778
- They'll put you in jail.
- Have to catch me first.

137
00:08:07,988 --> 00:08:09,905
Don't forget, Jerry,
you're on again at 4: 15.

138
00:08:10,115 --> 00:08:12,825
- Don't worry. I'll be back.
- These things take hours sometimes.

139
00:08:13,034 --> 00:08:15,035
My wife never held up a show in her life.

140
00:08:19,666 --> 00:08:21,584
[CHEERING CONTINUES]

141
00:08:31,136 --> 00:08:32,720
JERRY:
Excuse me, can I get through here?

142
00:08:32,929 --> 00:08:34,847
The Irish are at the head of the parade.

143
00:08:35,056 --> 00:08:38,142
- I'm not in the parade. I want to get through.
- Not a chance, brother.

144
00:08:45,984 --> 00:08:47,943
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

145
00:08:48,153 --> 00:08:50,279
You don't say so.
We'll get you there in a jiffy!

146
00:08:50,489 --> 00:08:52,740
Here, this'll give you courage. Charge!

147
00:09:02,250 --> 00:09:04,084
[JERRY PANTING]

148
00:09:05,837 --> 00:09:07,213
Nellie.

149
00:09:08,423 --> 00:09:09,381
Nellie.

150
00:09:18,141 --> 00:09:19,683
- Is she all right?
- She's doing fine.

151
00:09:19,893 --> 00:09:24,563
- What is it?
- Well, all signs point to its being a boy.

152
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:34,281
Wait. He just got here
and he's sleeping already.

153
00:09:34,991 --> 00:09:38,285
All babies sleep 20 hours a day, Jerry.

154
00:09:39,412 --> 00:09:41,455
That's why most of them
never amount to anything.

155
00:09:41,665 --> 00:09:43,582
- What'll we call him?
- Oh, I don't know.

156
00:09:43,792 --> 00:09:45,918
- What do you say?
- Well, seeing that he arrived...

157
00:09:46,127 --> 00:09:49,797
...on the Fourth of July,
what about George Washington Cohan?

158
00:09:50,632 --> 00:09:53,092
Well, it has a nice patriotic ring to it.
What do you think?

159
00:09:53,301 --> 00:09:56,178
Oh, the George is fine,
but the Washington...

160
00:09:56,388 --> 00:09:58,180
...may be too long for a billboard.

161
00:09:59,224 --> 00:10:01,809
Well, how about a nice short Irish name?
Dennis or Michael?

162
00:10:02,602 --> 00:10:07,273
George Michael Cohan. Heh.

163
00:10:07,482 --> 00:10:09,900
Yes, I like that name.

164
00:10:11,653 --> 00:10:12,695
Oh, gosh. I forgot.

165
00:10:16,950 --> 00:10:19,493
Hey! It's a boy!

166
00:10:22,539 --> 00:10:23,747
Oh, Jerry.

167
00:10:24,165 --> 00:10:26,083
[BABY CRYING]

168
00:10:29,588 --> 00:10:32,715
Heavenly day, Nellie!
He's crying with a brogue.

169
00:10:35,594 --> 00:10:38,220
GEORGE: The first thing I ever had
my fist on was the American flag.

170
00:10:38,430 --> 00:10:42,016
I hitched my wagon
to 38 stars and 13 stripes.

171
00:10:42,225 --> 00:10:45,352
I was 6 or 7 years old before I realized
they weren't celebrating my birthday...

172
00:10:45,562 --> 00:10:47,146
...on the Fourth of July.

173
00:10:47,814 --> 00:10:49,189
Then my folks had a real break...

174
00:10:49,399 --> 00:10:51,358
...when my little sister Josie
made her entrance.

175
00:10:51,568 --> 00:10:52,818
She grew to love show business...

176
00:10:53,028 --> 00:10:55,279
...just as she loved everybody
and everything.

177
00:10:55,488 --> 00:10:57,281
We toured the kerosene circuit
in a tank show...

178
00:10:57,490 --> 00:11:00,117
...called Daniel Boone on the Trail.

179
00:11:00,327 --> 00:11:04,288
Everybody doubled in brass.
Dad walloped the bass drum.

180
00:11:04,497 --> 00:11:06,624
For some reason,
they teamed me with a donkey.

181
00:11:06,833 --> 00:11:08,334
I was a good Democrat
even in those days.

182
00:11:08,543 --> 00:11:10,586
Mother and Josie threw out handbills.

183
00:11:10,795 --> 00:11:13,422
Their smiles would've sold tickets
to wooden Indians.

184
00:11:13,632 --> 00:11:16,467
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

185
00:11:16,676 --> 00:11:18,302
They kept putting new stars on the flag...

186
00:11:18,511 --> 00:11:21,138
...and the Cohans kept rushing out
to meet them.

187
00:11:21,848 --> 00:11:25,809
We had jokes to match every cornfield.
We sang at every milk station.

188
00:11:26,019 --> 00:11:27,978
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

189
00:11:28,897 --> 00:11:30,856
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING MERRY MUSIC]

190
00:11:33,568 --> 00:11:35,736
[SINGING]
Larry O'Leary is me name

191
00:11:35,945 --> 00:11:38,322
By trade, I am a dancing master

192
00:11:38,531 --> 00:11:41,492
There's no one can teach the same

193
00:11:42,118 --> 00:11:43,869
Or teach it

194
00:11:44,079 --> 00:11:47,623
Any faster

195
00:11:47,832 --> 00:11:51,585
It's easy, very easy

196
00:11:51,795 --> 00:11:55,047
If you watch every twist, every turn

197
00:11:55,256 --> 00:11:58,801
Keep your eyes upon me
And surprised you will be

198
00:11:59,010 --> 00:12:02,429
At the dancing you have yet to learn

199
00:12:02,972 --> 00:12:04,932
[FIDDLE SCREECHING]

200
00:12:10,230 --> 00:12:13,774
Keep your eyes upon me
And surprised you will be

201
00:12:13,983 --> 00:12:17,611
At the dancing you have yet to learn

202
00:12:20,990 --> 00:12:22,950
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

203
00:12:30,208 --> 00:12:32,126
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING MERRY MUSIC]

204
00:12:37,841 --> 00:12:39,383
[SINGING]
I was taken by surprise

205
00:12:39,592 --> 00:12:41,552
By a pair of roguish eyes

206
00:12:41,761 --> 00:12:45,139
While strolling through the park one day

207
00:12:45,974 --> 00:12:49,184
GEORGE: We trouped through depression
and inflation, the country's growing pains.

208
00:12:49,394 --> 00:12:51,186
Froze in winter
and roasted in summer.

209
00:12:51,396 --> 00:12:53,063
But it was a good life.

210
00:12:53,273 --> 00:12:55,733
It's a lucky family
that dances together every day.

211
00:12:55,942 --> 00:12:57,901
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING MERRY MUSIC]

212
00:13:17,130 --> 00:13:19,089
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

213
00:13:21,718 --> 00:13:24,178
1891 found our fortunes
flat as a pancake.

214
00:13:24,387 --> 00:13:26,680
Then came a bolt from the blue,
jobs for the whole family...

215
00:13:26,890 --> 00:13:28,891
...in a show called Peck's Bad Boy.

216
00:13:29,100 --> 00:13:31,894
We opened in Brooklyn.
Heh-heh-heh.

217
00:13:32,103 --> 00:13:35,189
The town was known for its spirited audiences
even before it had a ball team.

218
00:13:39,319 --> 00:13:42,529
JERRY: Who keeps hammering
on our opening night?

219
00:13:42,739 --> 00:13:44,907
- What are you doing here?
- I'm the star, ain't I?

220
00:13:45,116 --> 00:13:46,533
You have the leading part, yes.

221
00:13:46,743 --> 00:13:49,036
That means I'm a star,
and there should be a star...

222
00:13:49,245 --> 00:13:51,622
...on my dressing room door.
That's the law of the theater.

223
00:13:51,831 --> 00:13:53,540
Yes, Jerry, give the devil his due.

224
00:13:53,750 --> 00:13:57,419
I know, but I'm nervous. I'll go blank.
I won't be able to remember a line.

225
00:13:57,629 --> 00:13:58,670
Don't worry, Dad.

226
00:13:58,880 --> 00:14:01,423
If you stick, I'll throw you a line.
And you too, mother.

227
00:14:01,633 --> 00:14:03,592
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

228
00:14:06,471 --> 00:14:08,430
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING BRASSY MUSIC]

229
00:14:09,015 --> 00:14:10,974
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

230
00:14:25,323 --> 00:14:27,574
[SCHULTS YELLING INDISTINCTLY]

231
00:14:27,784 --> 00:14:30,828
SCHULTS:
Oh! Thief! Thief! Out! Out!

232
00:14:36,668 --> 00:14:38,085
[YELLING INDISTINCTLY]

233
00:14:47,011 --> 00:14:48,804
[SCHULTS YELLING INDISTINCTLY]

234
00:14:52,433 --> 00:14:54,518
SCHULTS:
Why do you do this to me?

235
00:14:54,727 --> 00:14:56,186
COP:
It's to jail you're going, me boy!

236
00:14:56,396 --> 00:14:59,022
JERRY: There, there, there, now.
Henry's not really a bad boy.

237
00:14:59,232 --> 00:15:00,899
He's just mischievous, that's all.

238
00:15:01,109 --> 00:15:04,027
Mr. Schults, I think that should take care
of the damage. Don't you think?

239
00:15:04,237 --> 00:15:06,697
Henry, I want you to promise
the cop and Mr. Schults...

240
00:15:06,906 --> 00:15:09,700
...that from now on
you'll always be a good boy.

241
00:15:09,909 --> 00:15:12,995
I'll promise,
but I can still lick any kid in town!

242
00:15:13,204 --> 00:15:14,371
[KIDS JEERING]

243
00:15:35,768 --> 00:15:37,728
- Fine work, Georgie.
NELLIE: I'm proud of you.

244
00:15:37,937 --> 00:15:40,480
- Great, Georgie, great.
- Nice going, kid.

245
00:15:40,690 --> 00:15:43,066
- Real piece of acting there, Georgie.
- You're going places.

246
00:15:43,276 --> 00:15:45,319
- Boy, he sure rolled them in the aisles.
- Thanks.

247
00:15:45,528 --> 00:15:47,237
But what are you all so surprised about?

248
00:15:47,447 --> 00:15:50,032
You could've told during rehearsals
that I'd be a sensation.

249
00:15:50,241 --> 00:15:53,076
Listen, there's nothing
to this acting business.

250
00:15:53,286 --> 00:15:56,246
I wonder what took me so long
to become a star.

251
00:15:56,456 --> 00:15:58,123
Excuse me. Hey, Vance.

252
00:15:58,333 --> 00:16:00,125
Call a rehearsal
for 10:00 tomorrow morning.

253
00:16:00,335 --> 00:16:02,544
Jerry, the time has come
for George's first spanking.

254
00:16:02,754 --> 00:16:04,713
That's right.
I'll hold him while you hit him.

255
00:16:04,923 --> 00:16:07,507
Not me. I don't hit hard enough
to make an impression.

256
00:16:07,717 --> 00:16:10,719
I can't do it. He'd think I'm jealous
because he got more laughs than I did.

257
00:16:10,929 --> 00:16:13,055
Don't think I'm not, either.

258
00:16:13,932 --> 00:16:17,351
Uh, several gentlemen
to see you outside, Mr. Cohan.

259
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:19,436
Oh.

260
00:16:19,646 --> 00:16:21,647
Gentlemen of the press, I presume?

261
00:16:21,856 --> 00:16:25,192
It's started already.
Will you excuse me?

262
00:16:28,738 --> 00:16:30,280
KID:
Let's see how tough he is!

263
00:16:32,325 --> 00:16:34,284
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

264
00:16:34,827 --> 00:16:37,454
GEORGE [SCREAMING]:
Ow! Ow! Ow!

265
00:16:41,668 --> 00:16:44,920
Ought to be arrested,
every one of those hoodlums.

266
00:16:45,129 --> 00:16:48,006
It seems to me you're taking
all this very calmly, Jerry Cohan.

267
00:16:48,216 --> 00:16:51,176
Your own son almost murdered
in cold blood.

268
00:16:51,386 --> 00:16:53,929
Well, the way I figure,
it's a fine tribute to Georgie's acting.

269
00:16:54,138 --> 00:16:56,640
The way he plays the part,
every kid will want to take a punch...

270
00:16:56,849 --> 00:16:58,892
...at Peck's bad boy
just to see what happens.

271
00:16:59,102 --> 00:17:01,645
What?! Have I got to go
through that every night?

272
00:17:01,854 --> 00:17:04,982
Yes. And matinees Wednesdays
and Saturdays.

273
00:17:05,525 --> 00:17:07,818
Georgie, those boys did you a great favor...

274
00:17:08,027 --> 00:17:10,237
...and they saved me a lot of trouble.

275
00:17:10,446 --> 00:17:14,032
You know, most actors give their whole lives
to their profession, not once scoring a hit.

276
00:17:14,242 --> 00:17:16,284
You're lucky.
You're a hit at the age of 13.

277
00:17:16,703 --> 00:17:19,329
I've been in this business a long time
and never met a performer...

278
00:17:19,539 --> 00:17:23,125
...who, in the long run, wouldn't rather be
a great guy than a great actor.

279
00:17:23,334 --> 00:17:25,210
That is, until I made your acquaintance.

280
00:17:26,170 --> 00:17:27,295
Can't I be both?

281
00:17:27,505 --> 00:17:30,382
Chances are, the way you're going,
you won't be either.

282
00:17:30,591 --> 00:17:33,051
If the hoodlums don't get you,
a committee of actors will.

283
00:17:33,261 --> 00:17:36,805
Actors are considered a very bad risk
by insurance companies.

284
00:17:37,015 --> 00:17:38,765
And any actor with a conceit like yours...

285
00:17:38,975 --> 00:17:41,727
...well, we just couldn't afford the premium.

286
00:17:41,936 --> 00:17:44,271
What your father really means
is you're too sensitive.

287
00:17:44,480 --> 00:17:46,398
You're too anxious to make good.

288
00:17:46,607 --> 00:17:48,150
You love the theater too much.

289
00:17:48,359 --> 00:17:51,570
Oh, I know you can improve,
if you want to.

290
00:17:51,779 --> 00:17:53,530
Sure, I can. Just watch me.

291
00:17:53,740 --> 00:17:57,325
From now on I'm Peck's bad boy
only from 8:30 till 11 in the evening.

292
00:17:57,535 --> 00:17:59,745
- That's a boy, Georgie.
- I promise, Mother.

293
00:17:59,954 --> 00:18:03,331
And don't forget Wednesdays and Saturdays,
2:30 till 5.

294
00:18:03,541 --> 00:18:07,169
Yes, sir! And the other 21 and a half hours,
I pattern myself after dad.

295
00:18:07,378 --> 00:18:09,588
Heh-heh. Well, you could find
a better example...

296
00:18:09,797 --> 00:18:12,007
...but that's the general idea.

297
00:18:13,009 --> 00:18:16,344
Jerry, what do you know.
Ed Albee's coming backstage to see you.

298
00:18:16,554 --> 00:18:18,805
JERRY: Albee.
- That's B.F. Keys' partner!

299
00:18:19,015 --> 00:18:20,849
He's big-time vaudeville.
We're in the big time.

300
00:18:21,059 --> 00:18:23,351
He didn't send for us.
He's come here to see us.

301
00:18:23,561 --> 00:18:25,479
Maybe it'd be better
if I spoke business to him.

302
00:18:25,688 --> 00:18:28,231
Georgie, I thought you said
you were going to reform.

303
00:18:28,441 --> 00:18:29,399
I'm sorry.

304
00:18:29,609 --> 00:18:31,610
When he comes in here,
I want you to keep quiet.

305
00:18:31,819 --> 00:18:33,153
Look at the condition of this room.

306
00:18:33,362 --> 00:18:35,530
Josie, get the cheap makeup off the table.

307
00:18:35,740 --> 00:18:37,407
Hurry up!

308
00:18:37,617 --> 00:18:39,201
JOSIE:
Quick, Georgie!

309
00:18:39,410 --> 00:18:41,953
Get the stuff off that shelf there.
That's right.

310
00:18:42,622 --> 00:18:43,747
Hey, Albee'll be right in.

311
00:18:43,956 --> 00:18:45,457
He just stopped at the water cooler.

312
00:18:45,666 --> 00:18:47,626
Jerry, if he offers you a cigar,
don't take it.

313
00:18:47,835 --> 00:18:50,337
I'll take it. That'll impress him
if he thinks I can smoke.

314
00:18:50,546 --> 00:18:52,047
You get behind that curtain.
Hurry up!

315
00:18:52,256 --> 00:18:55,383
I don't want to hear a word out of you.
I don't even want to hear you breathe.

316
00:18:55,593 --> 00:18:57,969
Josie, fix the chairs. The other one.

317
00:18:58,679 --> 00:19:01,681
Here, take this. Oh, Jerry.

318
00:19:02,892 --> 00:19:05,268
- Sit down, Nellie. Sit down.
- All right.

319
00:19:08,731 --> 00:19:10,398
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

320
00:19:12,485 --> 00:19:13,777
Come in.

321
00:19:13,986 --> 00:19:15,737
Mr. E.F. Albee.

322
00:19:15,947 --> 00:19:17,447
- Hello, Cohan.
JERRY: Mr. Albee.

323
00:19:17,657 --> 00:19:18,990
- Meet Mrs. Cohan.
- How do you do?

324
00:19:19,200 --> 00:19:20,617
NELLIE: How do you do?
- Sit down.

325
00:19:20,827 --> 00:19:21,993
Thank you.

326
00:19:22,203 --> 00:19:25,497
I saw your show tonight. Not bad.

327
00:19:25,706 --> 00:19:27,249
Have a cigar?

328
00:19:27,458 --> 00:19:28,583
Uh, no, thanks.

329
00:19:28,793 --> 00:19:30,585
Your show is no good
for vaudeville...

330
00:19:30,795 --> 00:19:32,838
...but I've seen a lot worse
right here in Brooklyn.

331
00:19:33,047 --> 00:19:34,756
We're opening a new theater
in Philadelphia...

332
00:19:34,966 --> 00:19:36,550
...the Bijou, on the Fourth of July.

333
00:19:36,759 --> 00:19:39,719
If you can fix up a good vaudeville act,
we'll double your present salary...

334
00:19:39,929 --> 00:19:42,597
...give you 10 weeks' guarantee,
and third or fourth billing.

335
00:19:42,807 --> 00:19:45,767
- Double our salary?
- You'll be with the best in the country.

336
00:19:45,977 --> 00:19:49,729
Vesta Victoria, Eddie Foy,
Warren Volk, Charlie Case...

337
00:19:49,939 --> 00:19:50,981
Just a second.

338
00:19:52,358 --> 00:19:53,650
I'm George M. Cohan.

339
00:19:53,860 --> 00:19:56,111
You're opening a theater
in Philadelphia on July 4th?

340
00:19:56,320 --> 00:19:58,989
- Yes, that's right.
- That's my birthday.

341
00:19:59,198 --> 00:20:01,825
Heh. Well, that isn't why
we're opening the theater.

342
00:20:02,034 --> 00:20:04,244
The salary's all right,
but how have you got the nerve...

343
00:20:04,453 --> 00:20:07,164
...to offer us third or fourth billing
after my performance tonight?

344
00:20:08,541 --> 00:20:09,875
Is this kid in your show?

345
00:20:10,334 --> 00:20:11,668
Am I in the show?!

346
00:20:11,878 --> 00:20:13,545
Who do you think was Peck's bad boy?

347
00:20:13,754 --> 00:20:16,464
Oh, I beg your pardon.
I didn't quite recognize you.

348
00:20:16,674 --> 00:20:19,759
You didn't? Then maybe you're not
the showman you're cracked up to be.

349
00:20:19,969 --> 00:20:21,052
NELLIE AND JERRY:
George!

350
00:20:21,262 --> 00:20:23,180
Well, now, maybe I'm not.

351
00:20:23,389 --> 00:20:26,641
Maybe you're not quite ready
for the big time yet.

352
00:20:27,727 --> 00:20:31,146
Mrs. Cohan. Mr. Cohan. Good night.

353
00:20:31,355 --> 00:20:33,023
NELLIE: Good night.
JERRY: Uh, Mr. Albee.

354
00:20:35,026 --> 00:20:36,818
- How do you do, Mr. Albee?
MAN: Good evening.

355
00:20:37,028 --> 00:20:38,486
- Call you a carriage?
- If you will.

356
00:20:38,696 --> 00:20:40,614
Carriage for Mr. Albee!

357
00:20:41,741 --> 00:20:44,534
See what happens because you wouldn't
lay a hand on him all these years?

358
00:20:44,744 --> 00:20:47,495
A mother isn't supposed to punish.
She just gives her permission.

359
00:20:47,705 --> 00:20:49,581
Have I your permission?

360
00:20:49,790 --> 00:20:52,417
- You certainly have.
JERRY: Ahem.

361
00:20:52,627 --> 00:20:54,419
Don't you ought to get
my permission too, Dad?

362
00:20:54,629 --> 00:20:56,338
NELLIE: Not the hand!
He plays the violin.

363
00:20:56,547 --> 00:20:58,048
All right, not on the hand.

364
00:20:58,257 --> 00:21:00,050
Not on the mouth! He has to sing.

365
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:03,094
All right, not on the mouth.
Come here.

366
00:21:04,680 --> 00:21:06,097
Here's one place without any talent!

367
00:21:06,307 --> 00:21:08,558
[SCREAMING]
Ow! Ow! Ow!

368
00:21:13,814 --> 00:21:16,524
- Who were Lewis and Clark, George?
- Acrobats?

369
00:21:16,734 --> 00:21:18,735
Look at this swell write-up
we got in the clipper.

370
00:21:18,945 --> 00:21:21,821
GEORGE: You'd find us wherever
new states sprouted on the prairie.

371
00:21:22,031 --> 00:21:24,199
We played every town in America
that had a theater.

372
00:21:24,408 --> 00:21:25,659
Any mail for Mr. Cohan?

373
00:21:25,868 --> 00:21:27,410
No. Your father picked up his mail.

374
00:21:27,620 --> 00:21:29,746
I mean, for Mr. George M. Cohan.

375
00:21:30,581 --> 00:21:32,374
The next 10 years rushed by
like a circus train.

376
00:21:32,583 --> 00:21:35,835
Dad seemed content with the sticks,
but I was straining at the leash.

377
00:21:36,045 --> 00:21:37,212
Here's your mail, Mr. Cohan.

378
00:21:37,421 --> 00:21:39,839
Oh, thanks.
A couple of tickets for the show.

379
00:21:40,049 --> 00:21:41,216
We played stock in Buffalo.

380
00:21:41,425 --> 00:21:44,594
Being versatile,
I was playing my mother's father.

381
00:21:44,804 --> 00:21:46,513
NELLIE:
Oh, Daddy, he has left me.

382
00:21:46,722 --> 00:21:48,723
GEORGE:
All is for the best, my daughter.

383
00:21:48,933 --> 00:21:52,269
In life, we trip, but right ourselves.

384
00:21:52,478 --> 00:21:54,813
I was correct about man's love.

385
00:21:55,022 --> 00:21:58,817
First, he considers his pleasure
or his honor or his purse.

386
00:21:59,026 --> 00:22:02,529
And only secondly does he think
of the woman he says he loves.

387
00:22:02,738 --> 00:22:05,365
Now I must go life's journey alone...

388
00:22:05,574 --> 00:22:09,286
...and struggle on my weary way
to find peace.

389
00:22:09,495 --> 00:22:12,455
Courage, Emily, courage.

390
00:22:12,665 --> 00:22:15,333
Living has taught your father many things.

391
00:22:15,543 --> 00:22:19,587
Among them,
to take the bitter with the better.

392
00:22:19,797 --> 00:22:25,927
The road to happiness is paved
with heartaches and stones.

393
00:22:26,137 --> 00:22:27,929
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

394
00:22:28,139 --> 00:22:30,098
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING UP-TEMPO MUSIC]

395
00:22:48,075 --> 00:22:50,994
- Good luck, Josie.
- Thanks, Mom.

396
00:22:51,203 --> 00:22:52,495
They're all yours, sweetheart.

397
00:22:52,705 --> 00:22:54,039
Good luck, honey.

398
00:22:57,293 --> 00:22:59,252
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

399
00:23:22,068 --> 00:23:23,693
[SIGHS]

400
00:23:25,529 --> 00:23:28,990
Hey, George, there's a young lady,
would like to talk to you.

401
00:23:29,200 --> 00:23:30,158
Show her in.

402
00:23:30,951 --> 00:23:32,619
All right, Miss.

403
00:23:33,412 --> 00:23:36,164
- Mr. Cohan will see you.
- Thank you.

404
00:23:36,374 --> 00:23:37,874
He's all yours.

405
00:23:44,090 --> 00:23:46,633
I'm 18. I sing and I dance,
and I'm going to New York.

406
00:23:46,842 --> 00:23:48,176
Should I?

407
00:23:48,886 --> 00:23:52,722
Oh, Mr. Cohan, you're so old
and so experienced in the theater.

408
00:23:52,932 --> 00:23:55,183
So fatherly.

409
00:23:55,935 --> 00:23:57,894
[COUGHING]

410
00:23:59,980 --> 00:24:01,481
Do you think it's wise?

411
00:24:01,690 --> 00:24:05,777
I mean, my being 18, singing and dancing,
and going to New York?

412
00:24:05,986 --> 00:24:11,241
Well, ahem, that's very wise.
I mean, being 18 is very wise.

413
00:24:11,450 --> 00:24:12,784
And as for New York...

414
00:24:12,993 --> 00:24:15,745
...The Four Cohans open there this fall
with their new show...

415
00:24:15,955 --> 00:24:18,665
...with a new cyclorama
and 2 carloads of scenery.

416
00:24:18,874 --> 00:24:20,250
Really? When are you leaving here?

417
00:24:20,459 --> 00:24:24,212
- Tomorrow night, right after the show.
- Oh. I can't leave till Wednesday.

418
00:24:24,422 --> 00:24:28,967
- I graduate from high school Tuesday.
- Oh. That's too bad.

419
00:24:29,176 --> 00:24:31,344
Oh, Georgie... Uh, excuse me.

420
00:24:31,554 --> 00:24:33,221
You haven't forgotten
we have a date tonight?

421
00:24:33,431 --> 00:24:35,223
Oh, no, no, no.
Of course not.

422
00:24:35,433 --> 00:24:36,724
We're going roller-skating.

423
00:24:36,934 --> 00:24:39,102
Roller-skating on a night like this?

424
00:24:39,311 --> 00:24:40,770
Why, there's a moon out.

425
00:24:40,980 --> 00:24:43,148
I'll be ready in five minutes.

426
00:24:44,442 --> 00:24:46,109
[GEORGE CHUCKLES]

427
00:24:46,318 --> 00:24:47,444
Pipperino, isn't she?

428
00:24:47,653 --> 00:24:50,822
- Yes. Is she your daughter?
- Oh, I'm not married.

429
00:24:51,031 --> 00:24:53,533
- Your niece, perhaps?
- No, she's just a kid with the show.

430
00:24:53,742 --> 00:24:54,701
We've been dating.

431
00:24:54,910 --> 00:24:56,327
[CLICKS TONGUE]

432
00:24:56,537 --> 00:24:58,455
Isn't she a little too young for you?

433
00:24:58,664 --> 00:25:02,417
No. She's getting along in years.
She's 17.

434
00:25:03,002 --> 00:25:04,085
[MARY SIGHS]

435
00:25:04,295 --> 00:25:06,087
Well, shall I sing for you?

436
00:25:06,297 --> 00:25:09,174
I know I have talent,
even if I am from Buffalo.

437
00:25:09,383 --> 00:25:11,134
Well, we haven't got any piano handy.

438
00:25:11,343 --> 00:25:13,052
Well, I'll dance.

439
00:25:17,683 --> 00:25:19,476
GEORGE:
Mm-hm. Ahem.

440
00:25:19,685 --> 00:25:21,728
Well, uh, that's rather old, isn't it?

441
00:25:21,937 --> 00:25:24,772
Everybody's done that. You don't want
to be just an imitator, do you?

442
00:25:24,982 --> 00:25:27,650
Oh, no.
Here's a step I made up myself.

443
00:25:31,447 --> 00:25:32,447
But on the other hand...

444
00:25:32,656 --> 00:25:34,908
...you don't want to be too original either,
do you?

445
00:25:35,117 --> 00:25:36,659
- No.
- Well, I tell you what you do.

446
00:25:36,869 --> 00:25:40,246
You sit right here. You sit right here,
and I will give you an idea of what I mean.

447
00:25:40,456 --> 00:25:43,541
It may not be much. I'm not the dancer
I used to be, but then who is?

448
00:25:43,751 --> 00:25:45,668
Now, watch carefully now.

449
00:25:48,547 --> 00:25:49,797
Oh, no, no!

450
00:25:50,007 --> 00:25:52,675
- Don't you like it?
- Oh, but your heart!

451
00:25:55,596 --> 00:25:58,264
My heart is every bit
as good as it ever was.

452
00:25:59,558 --> 00:26:01,309
Oh, so fast!

453
00:26:01,519 --> 00:26:04,479
Such excitement, at your age.

454
00:26:04,688 --> 00:26:05,813
Sit down and rest.

455
00:26:06,023 --> 00:26:07,899
Maybe I have overdone it a little.

456
00:26:08,108 --> 00:26:11,027
Oh, look at the perspiration
on your brow.

457
00:26:11,737 --> 00:26:14,322
Your wrinkles.
What happened to your wrinkles?

458
00:26:14,532 --> 00:26:18,034
Well, I do have to make up older
than I actually am, you know.

459
00:26:18,244 --> 00:26:20,036
- How old are you?
- Eh...

460
00:26:20,246 --> 00:26:21,371
Not yet 70.

461
00:26:22,331 --> 00:26:24,374
You seem different
from when I first came in.

462
00:26:24,583 --> 00:26:25,875
Even your voice sounds younger.

463
00:26:26,085 --> 00:26:27,502
Well, you see, it's a gift I have.

464
00:26:27,711 --> 00:26:29,462
I'm always as young
as the people I'm with...

465
00:26:29,672 --> 00:26:31,339
...and you've made me feel very young.

466
00:26:31,549 --> 00:26:32,507
[CLICKS TONGUE]

467
00:26:32,716 --> 00:26:35,593
- Very young. Heh-heh-heh.
- I'm glad.

468
00:26:35,803 --> 00:26:37,679
Well, now, let's make plans.

469
00:26:37,888 --> 00:26:39,681
Which manager
should I take you to see first?

470
00:26:39,890 --> 00:26:41,683
Uh, Klaw and Erlanger?

471
00:26:41,892 --> 00:26:45,645
Good old Abe's a very nice fellow,
but maybe a little bit too soon.

472
00:26:45,854 --> 00:26:47,647
Uh, Tony Pastor?

473
00:26:47,856 --> 00:26:49,190
Well, that's better.

474
00:26:49,400 --> 00:26:51,150
Albee, Coster, Beale, and Proctor...

475
00:26:51,360 --> 00:26:53,111
- Oh!
GEORGE: Huh?

476
00:26:53,320 --> 00:26:55,321
- Ooh!
- Oh!

477
00:26:55,531 --> 00:26:56,573
Wait a minute, little girl.

478
00:26:56,782 --> 00:26:59,242
You're not gonna let a beard
and eyebrows frighten you, are you?

479
00:26:59,451 --> 00:27:01,244
In show business,
you'll see a lot of those.

480
00:27:01,453 --> 00:27:03,913
I'm not sure I want to go
into show business now.

481
00:27:04,123 --> 00:27:05,373
With your talent and ability?

482
00:27:05,583 --> 00:27:08,126
There are very few around
who can sing and dance and act too.

483
00:27:08,335 --> 00:27:10,795
How do you know I can do all those things?
You've never seen me.

484
00:27:11,005 --> 00:27:13,590
I don't have to. I can tell a trouper
a mile away, right on sight.

485
00:27:13,799 --> 00:27:15,675
I feel as though I've known you for years.

486
00:27:15,884 --> 00:27:17,302
- What's your name?
- Mary.

487
00:27:17,511 --> 00:27:20,888
That's a very pretty name, a very pretty name.
Now, Mary, you calm down.

488
00:27:21,098 --> 00:27:23,558
Let's have a bite to eat, huh?
I always eat after the last show.

489
00:27:23,767 --> 00:27:25,018
- Are you hungry?
- Yes.

490
00:27:25,227 --> 00:27:28,896
I've been here since 2:00 this afternoon,
trying to get up courage to come backstage.

491
00:27:29,106 --> 00:27:31,274
You must be hungry after seven shows.

492
00:27:31,483 --> 00:27:33,109
We'll have a nice cold bottle and a bird.

493
00:27:33,819 --> 00:27:34,861
What's a cold bottle?

494
00:27:36,113 --> 00:27:38,615
In show business we call that
a piece of pie and a glass of milk.

495
00:27:39,825 --> 00:27:42,994
Aren't you going roller-skating
with that, tlick-tlick, Pipperino?

496
00:27:43,203 --> 00:27:44,996
Nah, I'm tired of picking her up.

497
00:27:45,205 --> 00:27:46,789
[GASPS]

498
00:27:46,957 --> 00:27:48,666
- What's the matter, Mary?
- Oh!

499
00:27:50,210 --> 00:27:51,377
Got it.

500
00:27:56,300 --> 00:27:58,259
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING MERRY MUSIC]

501
00:27:58,469 --> 00:28:01,262
ALL [SINGING]:
I was born in Virginia

502
00:28:01,472 --> 00:28:04,057
That's the state that will win ya

503
00:28:04,266 --> 00:28:07,310
If you've got a soul in ya

504
00:28:07,519 --> 00:28:10,313
Ain't no southern frown

505
00:28:10,522 --> 00:28:13,399
WOMEN:
In the city of Norfolk

506
00:28:13,609 --> 00:28:16,361
MEN:
Home of beauties and war talk

507
00:28:16,570 --> 00:28:18,988
WOMEN: Reckon you'll like it
MEN: If you should strike it

508
00:28:19,198 --> 00:28:22,617
ALL:
That doggone town

509
00:28:46,517 --> 00:28:49,686
Pretty good. There's a contract
in my desk already made out.

510
00:28:49,895 --> 00:28:51,979
Go and get it. Say.

511
00:28:52,189 --> 00:28:55,358
If any of the Cohans ask you how you like
their act, just tell them it was fair.

512
00:28:55,567 --> 00:28:56,526
I get you.

513
00:29:10,416 --> 00:29:12,333
[COHANS WHISTLING TO MUSIC]

514
00:29:28,892 --> 00:29:31,060
Reckon you'll like it
If you should strike it

515
00:29:31,270 --> 00:29:34,063
That doggone town

516
00:29:34,273 --> 00:29:36,232
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

517
00:29:42,906 --> 00:29:44,866
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

518
00:29:52,082 --> 00:29:53,791
Ladies and gentlemen...

519
00:29:54,126 --> 00:29:55,960
...my mother thanks you...

520
00:29:56,420 --> 00:29:58,337
...my father thanks you...

521
00:29:58,756 --> 00:30:00,590
...my sister thanks you...

522
00:30:01,175 --> 00:30:02,925
...and I thank you.

523
00:30:08,849 --> 00:30:10,057
WOMAN:
Nice going.

524
00:30:10,267 --> 00:30:12,602
That's tearing them out of their chairs.

525
00:30:12,811 --> 00:30:14,228
All set up for you, boys.
Go get them.

526
00:30:14,438 --> 00:30:17,315
Oh, Dad, after the way we went tonight,
we're certainly ready for New York.

527
00:30:17,524 --> 00:30:19,609
If we're a hit here,
it's a cinch in New York.

528
00:30:19,818 --> 00:30:21,277
- Nice going, kid.
- Thanks.

529
00:30:21,487 --> 00:30:24,280
Oh, uh, Mr. Cohan, just a minute.

530
00:30:24,490 --> 00:30:26,949
- Pretty fair act you folks have got.
- They seemed to like it.

531
00:30:27,159 --> 00:30:28,951
That's a soft audience.
Got any open time?

532
00:30:29,161 --> 00:30:31,078
- Yes, from now on.
- I'd like to make you an offer.

533
00:30:31,288 --> 00:30:33,706
- We'd be glad to talk about it.
- Fine. Fine. Heh.

534
00:30:33,916 --> 00:30:36,834
You know, they're always a soft audience here
on Wednesday. Pushover.

535
00:30:39,463 --> 00:30:40,880
[CLICKS TONGUE]

536
00:30:41,089 --> 00:30:42,715
- Oh. Mm-hm.
- Did you catch it?

537
00:30:42,925 --> 00:30:44,217
Oh, you were wonderful, George.

538
00:30:44,426 --> 00:30:46,511
- But I don't know. I miss that beard.
- Uh-huh.

539
00:30:46,720 --> 00:30:49,263
- Did you get up on that number?
- Yes. It's a lovely song, George.

540
00:30:49,473 --> 00:30:50,890
- I've learned it by heart.
- Good.

541
00:30:51,099 --> 00:30:53,434
I did it with the orchestra leader,
and you do it this show.

542
00:30:53,644 --> 00:30:55,937
He knows your key,
and you just follow him for tempo.

543
00:30:56,146 --> 00:30:59,357
There's a notice on the call-board.
You can't change your act after the first show.

544
00:30:59,566 --> 00:31:02,318
The manager expects me to sing
"The Wedding of the Lily and the Rose."

545
00:31:02,528 --> 00:31:04,695
Who were they applauding out there,
the manager or me?

546
00:31:04,905 --> 00:31:08,324
- Now, go on out there and do it.
- Oh, George, I can't move.

547
00:31:08,534 --> 00:31:10,993
I can't go out there,
not without rehearsal.

548
00:31:11,203 --> 00:31:12,453
What are you worried about?

549
00:31:12,663 --> 00:31:15,289
You're doing a George M. Cohan lyric
to a George M. Cohan melody.

550
00:31:15,958 --> 00:31:17,291
Yes, but it's my voice.

551
00:31:17,501 --> 00:31:20,378
A George M. Cohan discovery.
Nobody ever had a better start.

552
00:31:21,338 --> 00:31:23,422
There's your introduction. Go on.

553
00:31:23,632 --> 00:31:25,591
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING MERRY MUSIC]

554
00:31:28,846 --> 00:31:30,471
Good luck, kid.

555
00:31:30,681 --> 00:31:32,640
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

556
00:31:37,187 --> 00:31:40,648
[SINGING] When they see it coming
All them babies take a chill

557
00:31:40,858 --> 00:31:44,110
Diamonds glistening all around
And style enough to kill

558
00:31:44,319 --> 00:31:47,738
Her steady fella broke a dice game
Down in Louisville

559
00:31:47,948 --> 00:31:51,617
And buys her chicken every day for lunch
"Come seven"

560
00:31:51,827 --> 00:31:55,288
Dreamy eyes that sparkle
And she rolls them mighty cute

561
00:31:55,497 --> 00:31:58,499
Colored gentlemen say
"That lady certainly is a beaut"

562
00:31:58,709 --> 00:32:00,751
Go broke that she's a hot potato

563
00:32:00,961 --> 00:32:02,670
She's a red-hot radiator

564
00:32:02,880 --> 00:32:05,673
She's the warmest baby in the bunch

565
00:32:11,013 --> 00:32:13,890
Ten consecutive weeks in New York.
That's the big time.

566
00:32:14,099 --> 00:32:16,726
When you leave New York,
Philadelphia, Boston...

567
00:32:16,935 --> 00:32:19,770
- Let me take a look at that.
- Excuse me.

568
00:32:20,647 --> 00:32:22,732
What's going on here?
Take your makeup off.

569
00:32:22,941 --> 00:32:24,984
I'll be back in just a minute.

570
00:32:25,193 --> 00:32:28,070
MARY: Colored gentlemen say
"That lady certainly is a beaut"

571
00:32:28,280 --> 00:32:31,198
Go broke that she's a hot potato
She's a red-hot radiator

572
00:32:31,408 --> 00:32:34,410
Hey, Bill. What is this?
What's she singing?

573
00:32:34,620 --> 00:32:36,037
Who told her to switch that number?

574
00:32:36,246 --> 00:32:38,581
She's supposed to sing
"The Wedding of the Lily and the Rose."

575
00:32:38,790 --> 00:32:41,083
- Now, who told her to switch that number?
- I don't know.

576
00:32:41,293 --> 00:32:43,169
You don't know?

577
00:32:43,378 --> 00:32:45,296
Bring down that curtain!

578
00:32:45,505 --> 00:32:48,424
Pull out the houselights
as soon as she finishes the chorus.

579
00:32:48,634 --> 00:32:50,509
Give her a chance.
See how that song goes.

580
00:32:50,719 --> 00:32:52,762
The song is gone. Pull out the lights.

581
00:32:52,971 --> 00:32:54,722
- No, don't do it.
- Who does she think she is?

582
00:32:54,932 --> 00:32:58,267
Who does she think is running this theater?
What does she mean by changing her number?

583
00:32:58,477 --> 00:33:00,937
The only reason I put her on was
because the dog act got drunk.

584
00:33:01,146 --> 00:33:03,856
- He'll be all right in the morning.
- Oh, she was your idea.

585
00:33:04,066 --> 00:33:07,193
- And a very good idea too.
- Now I know who got the dog act drunk.

586
00:33:07,402 --> 00:33:10,446
Who, me? Why, I've never been
in a saloon in my life.

587
00:33:10,656 --> 00:33:12,281
And style enough to kill

588
00:33:12,491 --> 00:33:16,452
Her steady fella broke a dice game
Down in Louisville

589
00:33:16,662 --> 00:33:19,622
Now look at that. Could you ask
for anything more than that?

590
00:33:19,831 --> 00:33:22,708
Hmm? Just wait. She's wonderful, I think.
Don't you think so?

591
00:33:22,918 --> 00:33:25,086
- Don't do that!
- Ha-ha-ha!

592
00:33:25,295 --> 00:33:28,673
Don't do that! Pull out the lights.
Pull down that curtain.

593
00:33:28,882 --> 00:33:30,424
She...

594
00:33:30,634 --> 00:33:32,176
Get your props together.
You're on next.

595
00:33:32,386 --> 00:33:34,553
Hey, boys, start limbering up.
You follow the jugglers.

596
00:33:34,763 --> 00:33:37,515
You get that curtain up. You can't ring down
on a George M. Cohan song.

597
00:33:37,724 --> 00:33:40,935
A George M...? Oh, I see.

598
00:33:41,144 --> 00:33:42,812
Oh, it's your song. You wrote it.

599
00:33:43,021 --> 00:33:44,605
You can tell that by the applause.

600
00:33:44,815 --> 00:33:46,649
Now, Mary,
go out there and do an encore.

601
00:33:46,858 --> 00:33:49,276
- Do one more chorus, and really do it.
- Oh, no. No, you don't.

602
00:33:49,486 --> 00:33:52,196
Young lady, if you're gonna be
trying out any junk like that...

603
00:33:52,406 --> 00:33:55,741
...do it on a split-fee time, but you'll not
be singing songs like that in my theater.

604
00:33:55,951 --> 00:33:58,077
Now you take a little tip from me:
you start packing.

605
00:33:58,286 --> 00:34:01,497
If you've got any squawks, unload them on me.
I'm the one that started all this.

606
00:34:01,707 --> 00:34:05,501
Listen, squirt, any more interference
on your part and you'll be blacklisted.

607
00:34:05,711 --> 00:34:08,462
You won't even be able to get
into a stage door of any theater...

608
00:34:08,672 --> 00:34:10,631
...and what's more,
as for those songs of yours...

609
00:34:10,841 --> 00:34:12,633
...they won't even be played
on a hurdy-gurdy.

610
00:34:12,843 --> 00:34:14,927
- Are you trying to threaten me?
MARY: Oh!

611
00:34:15,137 --> 00:34:17,805
GEORGE: Mary! Mary!
Don't pay any attention to him now.

612
00:34:18,015 --> 00:34:19,473
Give me the key to your dressing room.

613
00:34:19,683 --> 00:34:22,143
Drunk or sober,
the dog act goes on in the next show.

614
00:34:22,352 --> 00:34:23,853
And look here...

615
00:34:28,025 --> 00:34:29,191
Bring down the curtain!

616
00:34:29,401 --> 00:34:31,360
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

617
00:34:33,447 --> 00:34:35,197
Cohan, you're fired.

618
00:34:35,407 --> 00:34:37,241
You're canceled!
You're washed up!

619
00:34:37,451 --> 00:34:40,036
You and your whole family!

620
00:34:41,747 --> 00:34:43,706
GEORGE:
Oh, things were tough.

621
00:34:43,915 --> 00:34:45,750
Well, at least I was in New York.

622
00:34:45,959 --> 00:34:47,752
I had a trunkful of songs
and play scripts...

623
00:34:47,961 --> 00:34:49,336
...and a heart full of confidence.

624
00:34:49,546 --> 00:34:51,047
I'm glad I had it.

625
00:34:52,340 --> 00:34:54,884
I'm sorry. I can't use this, Cohan.

626
00:34:56,219 --> 00:34:57,636
Youth needs confidence.

627
00:34:57,846 --> 00:35:01,140
I'd learned my job the hard way,
all over the United States.

628
00:35:01,349 --> 00:35:03,559
Guys who had never been past
the corner cigar store...

629
00:35:03,769 --> 00:35:05,603
...were saying my stuff was no good.

630
00:35:05,812 --> 00:35:08,314
A kid had to believe in himself
to buck that.

631
00:35:08,523 --> 00:35:10,483
[PIANO PLAYING JAUNTY MUSIC]

632
