Harrigan
That's me

659
00:36:45,412 --> 00:36:48,289
- Well, what do you think?
- I didn't like it. It didn't appeal to me.

660
00:36:48,498 --> 00:36:51,125
What do you mean, you?
I'm the senior partner around here.

661
00:36:51,334 --> 00:36:53,586
- I make the decisions.
- Well, what did you think?

662
00:36:53,795 --> 00:36:54,962
It didn't appeal to me, either.

663
00:36:55,630 --> 00:36:57,923
Which proves, gentlemen,
that you have no ear for music.

664
00:36:58,133 --> 00:37:00,134
He's got no ear for music.
I'm the senior partner.

665
00:37:00,343 --> 00:37:02,052
I have a wonderful ear for music.

666
00:37:03,013 --> 00:37:05,264
But what about the libretto?
It's a grand story, isn't it?

667
00:37:05,473 --> 00:37:07,349
- I laughed all the way through it.
- That's my cue.

668
00:37:07,559 --> 00:37:09,310
If Harold laughs,
then I know it isn't funny.

669
00:37:10,604 --> 00:37:12,688
Have Mr. Cohan sing
the rest of the score for you.

670
00:37:12,898 --> 00:37:15,357
Maybe you didn't like Harrigan
because I haven't got a voice.

671
00:37:15,567 --> 00:37:17,526
Oh, I think you have a lovely voice.

672
00:37:17,736 --> 00:37:20,529
- Don't you think so, Mr. Dietz?
- Yes, you have a very nice voice.

673
00:37:20,739 --> 00:37:22,615
In fact, if you'd like a job
answering our phone...

674
00:37:22,824 --> 00:37:25,284
Are you or are you not going
to produce my play?

675
00:37:25,493 --> 00:37:28,370
If you think I'd put any of my wife's money
into that trash, you're crazy.

676
00:37:28,580 --> 00:37:32,583
That's it, Mary. That's enough.
They've had their chance.

677
00:37:33,501 --> 00:37:35,419
- Have you an appointment?
- Yes. Sam Harris.

678
00:37:35,629 --> 00:37:38,172
I want to see them
about this melodrama I have.

679
00:37:38,381 --> 00:37:40,382
DIETZ:
We have no time to listen to that junk.

680
00:37:40,592 --> 00:37:42,593
You don't know it, boys,
but your days are numbered.

681
00:37:42,802 --> 00:37:44,261
You're making room
for the likes of me.

682
00:37:44,471 --> 00:37:47,848
And someday, Mr. Senior Partner, you're gonna
come to me and admit you were wrong.

683
00:37:48,850 --> 00:37:51,810
In 20 years of show business,
I never once admitted I was wrong.

684
00:37:52,020 --> 00:37:53,062
That's his department.

685
00:37:53,271 --> 00:37:55,856
- And as for your wife's money...
- Excuse me. I have an appointment.

686
00:37:56,066 --> 00:37:57,816
- Who are you?
- My name's Sam Harris.

687
00:37:58,026 --> 00:38:00,236
I have a melodrama here
called Wildflower.

688
00:38:00,445 --> 00:38:02,071
Wildflower.

689
00:38:03,031 --> 00:38:05,449
One, two, three, four, five,
six, seven, eight, nine, 10.

690
00:38:05,659 --> 00:38:07,826
- Horses.
- Oh, and Indians. Uh-oh.

691
00:38:08,036 --> 00:38:10,412
Don't let a couple of Gilberts
like that get under your skin.

692
00:38:10,622 --> 00:38:12,414
There's no sense in crying now.

693
00:38:12,624 --> 00:38:14,250
Buffalo is such a beautiful city.

694
00:38:14,459 --> 00:38:15,960
Is that what you're crying about?

695
00:38:16,169 --> 00:38:18,128
It's a beautiful city,
but I hate to go back to it.

696
00:38:18,338 --> 00:38:20,422
Don't worry. You won't have to.
I'll show them yet.

697
00:38:20,632 --> 00:38:22,591
I'm gonna have my name
up and down Broadway...

698
00:38:22,801 --> 00:38:26,220
...until I'm as well known as Hood's Sarsaparilla.
We'll whip them to a standstill.

699
00:38:26,429 --> 00:38:28,889
- Like Grant took Richmond.
- I never really thought of leaving.

700
00:38:29,099 --> 00:38:31,392
We'll make this whole business sit up
and holler for help.

701
00:38:31,601 --> 00:38:35,145
That's what we'll do.
They'll all hear from us, every one of them.

702
00:38:35,355 --> 00:38:37,481
DIETZ: I'm the senior partner.
I'll do the throwing out.

703
00:38:37,691 --> 00:38:39,775
SAM: You don't have to throw me out.
I know the way.

704
00:38:39,985 --> 00:38:42,278
That's the last time
I'll ever bring you a play.

705
00:38:43,571 --> 00:38:45,155
That's my department.

706
00:38:45,365 --> 00:38:48,575
Now I will take it to Klaw and Erlanger.
They don't always think of box office.

707
00:38:48,785 --> 00:38:50,286
Thanks.

708
00:38:50,495 --> 00:38:52,788
- Too expensive.
- Didn't even read the second act.

709
00:38:52,998 --> 00:38:55,040
Probably the biggest forest fire
ever put on the stage.

710
00:38:55,250 --> 00:38:56,709
[DOOR SLAMS]

711
00:38:56,918 --> 00:38:58,836
I think he's a little upset.

712
00:39:00,046 --> 00:39:04,133
Five-thirty. We'd have done eight shows
by this time in Buffalo.

713
00:39:09,806 --> 00:39:12,308
- The juggler just paid three weeks' back board.
- Oh!

714
00:39:12,517 --> 00:39:14,810
Put him at the head
so he doesn't have to reach.

715
00:39:15,020 --> 00:39:16,812
Where shall I put the magician?

716
00:39:17,022 --> 00:39:19,523
Until he's paid, he sits at the foot
of the table with the Cohans.

717
00:39:19,733 --> 00:39:21,066
Oh, starvation corner.

718
00:39:21,276 --> 00:39:23,902
And put the goulash at the head of the table
and keep everything...

719
00:39:24,112 --> 00:39:26,822
...but the noodles and the maple syrup
out of the reach of the Cohans.

720
00:39:27,032 --> 00:39:29,533
Noodles and syrup are just enough
to keep them alive.

721
00:39:29,743 --> 00:39:33,412
Anybody who owes me two months' board bill,
I just keep alive.

722
00:39:33,621 --> 00:39:35,497
I don't have to wait on them.

723
00:39:35,707 --> 00:39:37,624
[BELLS RINGING]

724
00:39:37,834 --> 00:39:39,835
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

725
00:39:40,045 --> 00:39:42,254
MAN 1: Good evening, Madame.
MAN 2: Good evening, Madame.

726
00:39:42,464 --> 00:39:44,798
Oh, no, no, no.

727
00:39:45,008 --> 00:39:47,468
- From now on, this is your seat.
- Oh, thank you.

728
00:39:47,677 --> 00:39:51,472
And you, master magician,
you sit over there with the Cohans.

729
00:39:51,681 --> 00:39:54,266
Heh. Madame, someday I hope
you will give me the pleasure...

730
00:39:54,476 --> 00:39:56,310
...of sawing you in half.

731
00:39:56,519 --> 00:39:58,354
- Ha-ha-ha!
- I just heard today...

732
00:39:58,563 --> 00:40:01,023
...that Hammerstein was bringing over
the Scotch actor...

733
00:40:01,232 --> 00:40:03,317
...Harry Lauter,
at 2500 bucks a week.

734
00:40:03,526 --> 00:40:07,196
Hammerstein's a great showman.
A lot of people have never seen a Scotchman.

735
00:40:07,405 --> 00:40:10,491
- Take some goulash, Mrs. Cohan.
NELLIE: Thank you.

736
00:40:10,700 --> 00:40:13,369
Did you have that appointment
with that man about your booking?

737
00:40:13,578 --> 00:40:16,038
Oh, yes, he's going to give work
to the act any day now.

738
00:40:16,247 --> 00:40:17,998
What happened
to that Boston offer you got?

739
00:40:18,208 --> 00:40:19,708
That was a mighty sweet proposition.

740
00:40:19,918 --> 00:40:23,003
Four weeks guaranteed at $300 a week
and top billing.

741
00:40:23,213 --> 00:40:25,714
Well, we didn't take it.
See, it just wasn't right.

742
00:40:25,924 --> 00:40:28,801
MADAME: Any act that lays off as long
as you have, any offer's all right.

743
00:40:29,010 --> 00:40:30,719
WOMAN:
Butter?

744
00:40:30,929 --> 00:40:33,305
We just thought we'd rest a few more weeks.

745
00:40:33,515 --> 00:40:36,016
Yes, you see, my brother's writing
some new material for us...

746
00:40:36,226 --> 00:40:38,227
...and, well, we're just not ready to open.

747
00:40:40,021 --> 00:40:41,271
MAN 1:
You're not fooling anybody.

748
00:40:41,481 --> 00:40:45,192
Everybody knows that you and Nellie and Josie
can get work anytime, anyplace. Heh.

749
00:40:45,402 --> 00:40:46,568
But nobody wants Georgie.

750
00:40:46,778 --> 00:40:49,905
MAN 2: Sure. He's made trouble
in every theater this side of San Francisco.

751
00:40:50,115 --> 00:40:53,659
MAN 3: You can't lay off just because
every manager has blackballed Georgie.

752
00:40:53,868 --> 00:40:55,911
His family hasn't blackballed him.

753
00:40:56,121 --> 00:40:58,622
We may have to take hard knocks
and make a lot of sacrifices...

754
00:40:58,832 --> 00:41:01,041
...but if they want our act,
they'll have to take him too.

755
00:41:01,251 --> 00:41:04,044
We're not breaking up our act
or our family. And besides...

756
00:41:04,254 --> 00:41:06,922
JERRY: All right, all right,
let the blackballs fall where they may.

757
00:41:07,132 --> 00:41:10,134
GEORGE: Madame Bartholdi,
champagne for everybody!

758
00:41:10,343 --> 00:41:11,510
[ALL MURMURING]

759
00:41:11,719 --> 00:41:13,804
- If I had it, who would pay for it?
- Dietz and Goff.

760
00:41:14,013 --> 00:41:17,015
- They're producing Little Johnny Jones.
NELLIE: Oh, George, really?

761
00:41:17,225 --> 00:41:21,270
When Dietz heard the music, he said to heck
with his wife's money, he's gonna use his own.

762
00:41:21,479 --> 00:41:23,439
A second round of champagne on me,
if you had any.

763
00:41:23,648 --> 00:41:26,358
Pass that goulash down
to this end of the table.

764
00:41:26,568 --> 00:41:28,527
Oh, George.

765
00:41:29,362 --> 00:41:30,863
Think of those billboards.

766
00:41:31,072 --> 00:41:34,575
Book, music and lyrics,
all by George M. Cohan.

767
00:41:35,076 --> 00:41:37,453
- Oh, Georgie, I...
- Oh, now, take it easy, Josie.

768
00:41:37,662 --> 00:41:40,289
- There's enough water in the goulash now.
- Heh-heh-heh.

769
00:41:40,498 --> 00:41:43,584
Oh, uh, Dad, I'm gonna be tied up
in rehearsal for the next few months.

770
00:41:43,793 --> 00:41:46,920
Why don't you and mom and Josie
take whatever offers in the meantime to fill in.

771
00:41:47,130 --> 00:41:49,923
Well, I hate to see the act split up, George,
but if you think so.

772
00:41:50,133 --> 00:41:52,968
Oh, sure. You can play all that stuff
around Chicago for Sullivan.

773
00:41:53,178 --> 00:41:54,761
The money's good,
and the jumps are short.

774
00:41:54,971 --> 00:41:58,223
It's a good idea.
You get tired resting too long.

775
00:41:58,433 --> 00:42:01,727
But it won't be the same going back
on the road without you, Georgie.

776
00:42:01,936 --> 00:42:04,688
Why, we'll be like a carriage
with only three wheels.

777
00:42:04,898 --> 00:42:08,317
But you will admit I was a bumpy wheel.
You'll roll along a whole lot easier without me.

778
00:42:08,526 --> 00:42:09,943
- Oh, no, Georgie.
- Oh, but you will.

779
00:42:10,153 --> 00:42:12,112
Is there a part in your play
for a bicycle rider?

780
00:42:12,322 --> 00:42:14,323
I used to be known
as "Venus on wheels."

781
00:42:14,532 --> 00:42:16,033
Mm-hm. I always knew
you weren't a cook.

782
00:42:16,242 --> 00:42:17,826
[MADAME LAUGHS]

783
00:42:21,789 --> 00:42:23,707
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

784
00:42:25,919 --> 00:42:28,545
- How's everything going, George?
- Not so good, kid. Not so good.

785
00:42:28,755 --> 00:42:31,381
I've been pounding the pavement so long,
my socks have bunions.

786
00:42:31,591 --> 00:42:34,259
- Say, Matt, would you put a head on that?
MATT: You bet I will.

787
00:42:34,469 --> 00:42:38,680
The villain says, "I'll tell the girl who you are
unless you help me hold up this train.

788
00:42:38,890 --> 00:42:40,307
Think fast. It's due in 10 minutes."

789
00:42:40,517 --> 00:42:42,601
You'll have the audience standing
with excitement.

790
00:42:42,810 --> 00:42:46,104
I know, I know. The hero helps him,
gets shot in the leg...

791
00:42:46,314 --> 00:42:48,440
...and the girl nurses him back to health.

792
00:42:48,650 --> 00:42:51,401
No, no, no. He gets shot in the arm,
Mr. Schwab, not the leg.

793
00:42:51,611 --> 00:42:54,530
- You know what happens next?
- I won't be in the theater to find out.

794
00:42:54,739 --> 00:42:57,115
I will be down the street
watching a musical comedy.

795
00:42:57,325 --> 00:42:59,952
Before I put $10,000 into a show...

796
00:43:00,161 --> 00:43:03,914
...it must have songs, dances,
and a lot of girls.

797
00:43:04,123 --> 00:43:08,502
Mmm! Women, women.
Little rose petals.

798
00:43:08,711 --> 00:43:11,922
Now, the big scene is where the hero saves
the girl from a burning forest fire.

799
00:43:12,131 --> 00:43:15,259
It won't be terribly expensive, Mr. Schwab.
I know where I can get a cheap fire.

800
00:43:15,468 --> 00:43:18,679
SCHWAB: You don't need much of a fire,
just enough to burn that manuscript.

801
00:43:18,888 --> 00:43:21,348
- Oh, here you are! I've been looking for you.
SAM: What?

802
00:43:21,558 --> 00:43:23,559
We gotta go to Dietz and Goff
and sign those papers.

803
00:43:23,768 --> 00:43:25,894
- Papers? What papers?
- What...? What papers?

804
00:43:26,104 --> 00:43:28,105
You don't want to talk about it
in front of Schwab.

805
00:43:28,314 --> 00:43:30,148
You haven't discussed our musical
with Schwab?

806
00:43:30,358 --> 00:43:32,067
- Music?
- We promised Dietz and Goff.

807
00:43:32,277 --> 00:43:33,819
I haven't said a word about a musical.

808
00:43:34,028 --> 00:43:36,113
Good. Dietz said it's the best musical
he's ever read.

809
00:43:36,322 --> 00:43:37,864
Even allowed Goff to agree with him.

810
00:43:38,074 --> 00:43:41,076
When I told him about those 20 ponies
and 20 showgirls all coming downstage...

811
00:43:41,286 --> 00:43:42,995
- Ponies and showgirls?
- Just a minute.

812
00:43:43,204 --> 00:43:45,247
- What are you talking about?
- Waiter, waiter!

813
00:43:45,456 --> 00:43:47,457
- Check for this table.
- No, no, no. That's mine.

814
00:43:47,667 --> 00:43:50,210
Oh, no, no...
Well, we won't argue about it.

815
00:43:50,420 --> 00:43:52,212
- Glad to have met you, Mr. Schwab.
- That's mine.

816
00:43:52,422 --> 00:43:55,132
- Come on, we can't keep Dietz waiting.
- You are a fine guy.

817
00:43:55,341 --> 00:43:56,550
You have girls up your sleeve.

818
00:43:56,759 --> 00:43:59,720
You have ponies and showgirls,
and you don't tell me about it?

819
00:43:59,929 --> 00:44:02,681
- What...? What's it about?
- We gave our word to Dietz.

820
00:44:02,890 --> 00:44:05,058
No time for details.
It's about Todd Sloan in London.

821
00:44:05,268 --> 00:44:06,935
- The famous jockey.
- Yeah. Come on, partner.

822
00:44:07,145 --> 00:44:10,981
Jockey? Jockey sounds swell.
Just my luck to miss out on it.

823
00:44:11,190 --> 00:44:15,110
Mmm. Well, good luck, boys.

824
00:44:18,573 --> 00:44:20,115
Oh, uh, you forgot your manuscript.

825
00:44:20,325 --> 00:44:23,035
Before we sign with Dietz and Goff,
I made some change in the lyric...

826
00:44:23,244 --> 00:44:24,995
...of "Yankee Doodle."
- "Yankee Doodle"?

827
00:44:25,204 --> 00:44:27,706
- It was perfect the way it was.
- Oh, you're gonna like this.

828
00:44:27,915 --> 00:44:31,043
- Gives the number added value. Watch...
- May I...? May I listen a little?

829
00:44:31,252 --> 00:44:33,462
- Well, think we should?
- I don't know.

830
00:44:33,671 --> 00:44:35,922
- If you promise to be quiet.
- I promise. I promise.

831
00:44:36,132 --> 00:44:39,009
All right. Come on.
There's a piano in the private room.

832
00:44:39,218 --> 00:44:40,260
"Yankee Doodle."

833
00:44:40,470 --> 00:44:41,928
"Yankee Doodle."

834
00:44:42,639 --> 00:44:44,056
Uh-huh. "Yankee Doodle Candy."

835
00:44:44,265 --> 00:44:45,724
Dandy. "Yankee Doodle Dandy."

836
00:44:45,933 --> 00:44:48,185
SCHWAB:
"Yankee Doodle Candy."

837
00:44:48,394 --> 00:44:50,354
[PLAYING PIANO]

838
00:44:52,106 --> 00:44:55,192
[SINGING]
I'm a Yankee Doodle Dandy

839
00:44:55,401 --> 00:44:58,487
Yankee Doodle
Do or die

840
00:44:58,696 --> 00:45:02,032
A real live nephew
Of my Uncle Sam

841
00:45:02,241 --> 00:45:04,785
Born on the Fourth of July

842
00:45:04,994 --> 00:45:09,039
I've got a Yankee Doodle sweetheart

843
00:45:09,248 --> 00:45:12,376
She's my Yankee Doodle joy

844
00:45:12,585 --> 00:45:15,962
Yankee Doodle came to London
Just to ride the ponies

845
00:45:16,172 --> 00:45:19,549
I am that Yankee Doodle boy

846
00:45:20,134 --> 00:45:21,301
I have heard enough.

847
00:45:21,511 --> 00:45:24,721
I will never forgive you for trying
to palm off a forest fire on me...

848
00:45:24,931 --> 00:45:26,640
...when you had that musical all the time.

849
00:45:26,849 --> 00:45:28,266
Yes, but we gave our word to Dietz.

850
00:45:28,518 --> 00:45:29,726
I can't understand it.

851
00:45:29,936 --> 00:45:33,438
Why is Dietz's wife's money
better than my wife's money?

852
00:45:33,648 --> 00:45:35,023
Why?

853
00:45:36,275 --> 00:45:38,193
Must you give it to Dietz and Goff?

854
00:45:38,403 --> 00:45:40,904
- Must you give it?
- Well, I don't know.

855
00:45:41,114 --> 00:45:42,781
I like Dietz,
but I'm not too fond of Goff.

856
00:45:42,990 --> 00:45:45,200
I'm crazy about Goff,
but I haven't got any use for Dietz.

857
00:45:45,410 --> 00:45:48,537
Gentlemen,
you are in perfect agreement.

858
00:45:48,746 --> 00:45:50,789
I will give you a check to bind the deal.

859
00:45:50,957 --> 00:45:52,374
Here.

860
00:45:53,543 --> 00:45:56,920
Thank you.
What's your partner's name?

861
00:45:57,130 --> 00:45:58,422
I don't know.

862
00:45:58,631 --> 00:46:00,257
[SAM AND SCHWAB LAUGH]

863
00:46:00,466 --> 00:46:02,426
SAM:
What's my partner's name? Ha-ha-ha!

864
00:46:02,635 --> 00:46:04,636
Well, don't toy with the kid
at a time like this.

865
00:46:04,846 --> 00:46:07,347
Tell him. George M. Cohan.

866
00:46:07,557 --> 00:46:11,059
George M. Cohan. C-O-H-A-N.

867
00:46:11,269 --> 00:46:13,145
And what is my junior partner's name?

868
00:46:13,354 --> 00:46:15,647
Sam H. Harris. Shake.

869
00:46:15,857 --> 00:46:19,151
- Hello. What should I write?
- Uh, Cohan and Harris.

870
00:46:19,360 --> 00:46:20,694
Cohan.

871
00:46:20,903 --> 00:46:24,072
- Mm-hm.
- And Harris.

