What it takes to win

919
00:50:09,340 --> 00:50:11,257
[BUGLE CALL TO RACE]

920
00:50:11,467 --> 00:50:13,426
[CROWD CHEERING]

921
00:50:15,930 --> 00:50:18,807
There they are, going to the post
All in good condition

922
00:50:19,016 --> 00:50:21,768
That's Yankee Doodle on the end
A wonderful position

923
00:50:21,978 --> 00:50:25,397
Look at him rear, he's broken line
He's simply wild to run

924
00:50:25,606 --> 00:50:28,316
Now they're back in line again
There's the starting gun

925
00:50:28,526 --> 00:50:30,527
CHORUS: They're off
Come on, Yankee Doodle

926
00:50:30,736 --> 00:50:33,655
We have bet the whole caboodle on you
Run, hurry up, hurry up, hurry up

927
00:50:33,864 --> 00:50:35,115
Yankee takes the lead

928
00:50:35,324 --> 00:50:37,534
Break away there
Show them how to earn their hay there

929
00:50:37,743 --> 00:50:40,453
How to run, hurry up, hurry up, hurry up
Show a little speed

930
00:50:40,663 --> 00:50:43,832
At the quarter, he's gaining
At the turn now, he's reining his horse

931
00:50:44,041 --> 00:50:46,292
Go, go, go, don't hold him back
Let him go

932
00:50:46,502 --> 00:50:49,462
At the half mark, he's cruising
But seems to be losing his lead

933
00:50:49,672 --> 00:50:51,881
Hurry up, hurry up, hurry up
You simply have to win

934
00:50:52,091 --> 00:50:54,676
He'll never win, he'll never win
The other nags are closing in

935
00:50:54,885 --> 00:50:57,679
- He's gone to third from second place
- Looks like he's thrown the race

936
00:50:57,888 --> 00:51:00,348
They've got him in a pocket
He can't get in the clear

937
00:51:00,558 --> 00:51:03,184
They're in the stretch, here they come
He's falling to the rear

938
00:51:03,394 --> 00:51:04,853
He's lost the race, but it's a frame

939
00:51:05,062 --> 00:51:08,690
We'll find the blighter who's to blame
And clear the name of Little Johnny Jones

940
00:51:08,899 --> 00:51:10,692
CROWD:
Aw!

941
00:51:10,901 --> 00:51:13,486
Well, that's it, ladies and gentlemen,
it's all over.

942
00:51:13,696 --> 00:51:15,947
Yankee Doodle let them down.

943
00:51:16,157 --> 00:51:18,158
So they'll either pasture him in clover...

944
00:51:18,367 --> 00:51:21,202
...or have him hauling rubbish
in London Town.

945
00:51:21,412 --> 00:51:23,455
CHORUS:
Good-bye, Johnny

946
00:51:23,664 --> 00:51:26,583
We're through with you

947
00:51:26,792 --> 00:51:32,005
We'll have nothing to do with you

948
00:51:32,214 --> 00:51:33,423
You've been dishonest.

949
00:51:33,632 --> 00:51:38,261
BOTH: And we find that you'll
be suspended for throwing the race.

950
00:51:39,680 --> 00:51:42,182
I'm a Yankee Doodle Dandy.

951
00:51:42,391 --> 00:51:44,684
[CHORUS HUMMING TO MUSIC]

952
00:51:44,894 --> 00:51:48,354
Yankee Doodle, do or die.

953
00:51:49,899 --> 00:51:53,234
Yankee Doodle came to London.

954
00:51:53,444 --> 00:51:55,737
Just to ride the ponies.

955
00:51:56,489 --> 00:51:59,574
I am that Yankee Doodle boy.

956
00:52:01,160 --> 00:52:06,331
CHORUS:
For he was that Yankee Doodle

957
00:52:06,540 --> 00:52:10,210
Boy

958
00:52:13,756 --> 00:52:15,632
Women, women. Little rose petals.

959
00:52:15,841 --> 00:52:18,134
Wonderful. You've got them eating
right out of your hand.

960
00:52:18,344 --> 00:52:19,719
- My congratulations.
- Thanks, Sam.

961
00:52:19,929 --> 00:52:21,888
As long as those critics
don't eat off my leg.

962
00:52:22,098 --> 00:52:24,808
Don't worry about the critics.
You got a smash hit. It's in the air.

963
00:52:25,017 --> 00:52:26,684
You can't stop anything
that's in the air.

964
00:52:26,894 --> 00:52:28,853
[ORCHESTRA RESUMES PLAYING]

965
00:52:40,741 --> 00:52:42,700
[HORN BLOWING]

966
00:52:54,421 --> 00:52:55,713
ALL [SINGING]:
All aboard

967
00:52:55,923 --> 00:52:58,007
We'll soon be sailing for

968
00:52:58,217 --> 00:53:01,386
The city of old New York

969
00:53:01,595 --> 00:53:04,597
Broadway nights
A million dancing lights

970
00:53:04,807 --> 00:53:08,560
Thrilling sights everywhere you walk

971
00:53:08,769 --> 00:53:12,021
London Town
We're bidding you adieu

972
00:53:12,231 --> 00:53:15,150
Gee, we hate to say good-bye to you

973
00:53:15,359 --> 00:53:16,734
All aboard

974
00:53:16,944 --> 00:53:18,653
Good-bye to London Town

975
00:53:18,863 --> 00:53:22,824
Hello to old Broadway

976
00:53:25,619 --> 00:53:27,453
All right, on the boat.

977
00:53:27,663 --> 00:53:29,956
Now, remember, Jones,
watch for the skyrocket.

978
00:53:30,166 --> 00:53:33,585
If it goes off, you'll know that I've obtained
certain papers from Ansty's cabin...

979
00:53:33,794 --> 00:53:36,296
...that'll prove you innocent
of throwing the English derby.

980
00:53:36,505 --> 00:53:38,256
It'll mean complete vindication.

981
00:53:38,465 --> 00:53:40,508
So stick here on the pier
and watch for the skyrocket.

982
00:53:40,718 --> 00:53:42,719
Thanks, pal. I'll be watching.

983
00:53:53,564 --> 00:53:56,149
Good-bye, Johnny. And don't worry,
we still believe in you.

984
00:53:56,358 --> 00:53:57,859
Thanks, kid. That'll help a lot.

985
00:53:58,068 --> 00:54:00,028
- Good-bye.
- Bye.

986
00:54:09,246 --> 00:54:11,247
[SINGING]
Give my regards

987
00:54:11,457 --> 00:54:12,832
To Broadway

988
00:54:13,042 --> 00:54:16,002
Remember me to Herald Square

989
00:54:17,421 --> 00:54:21,591
Tell all the gang
At 42nd Street

990
00:54:21,800 --> 00:54:25,011
That I will soon be there

991
00:54:25,763 --> 00:54:29,098
Whisper of how I am yearning

992
00:54:29,308 --> 00:54:33,645
To mingle with that old-time throng

993
00:54:33,854 --> 00:54:36,022
Give my regards

994
00:54:36,232 --> 00:54:40,693
To old Broadway
And say that I'll be there ere long

995
00:54:40,903 --> 00:54:42,070
[HORN BLOWING]

996
00:54:42,279 --> 00:54:46,908
CHORUS:
We'll give your regards to Broadway

997
00:54:47,117 --> 00:54:51,246
Remember you to Herald Square

998
00:54:51,455 --> 00:54:56,209
We'll tell all the gang
At 42nd Street

999
00:54:56,418 --> 00:55:00,838
That you will soon be there

1000
00:55:01,048 --> 00:55:05,385
We'll whisper of how you're yearning

1001
00:55:05,594 --> 00:55:09,472
To mingle with the old-time throng

1002
00:55:09,682 --> 00:55:12,267
We'll give your regards

1003
00:55:12,476 --> 00:55:14,435
To old Broadway

1004
00:55:14,645 --> 00:55:19,524
And say that you'll be there ere long

1005
00:55:20,651 --> 00:55:22,610
[SINGERS HUMMING TO MUSIC]

1006
00:55:37,626 --> 00:55:42,255
We'll whisper of how you're yearning

1007
00:55:42,464 --> 00:55:46,426
To mingle with the old-time throng

1008
00:55:46,635 --> 00:55:48,678
We'll give your regards

1009
00:55:48,887 --> 00:55:50,596
To old Broadway

1010
00:55:50,806 --> 00:55:55,601
And say that you'll be there ere long

1011
00:56:01,358 --> 00:56:03,151
Ha-ha!

1012
00:56:37,394 --> 00:56:41,147
We'll whisper of how you're yearning

1013
00:56:41,357 --> 00:56:44,859
To mingle with the old-time throng

1014
00:56:45,069 --> 00:56:48,613
We'll give your regards
To old Broadway

1015
00:56:48,822 --> 00:56:53,493
And say that you'll be there ere long

1016
00:57:04,338 --> 00:57:06,297
That was your department.

1017
00:57:08,675 --> 00:57:10,802
Is it the robin that heralds
the first breath of spring?

1018
00:57:11,011 --> 00:57:14,972
How can you think of robins in the spring
when we're freezing to death in Illinois?

1019
00:57:15,182 --> 00:57:18,059
MAN: Hey, Jerry, did you see the way
they're billing you in Waukegan?

1020
00:57:18,268 --> 00:57:21,437
Come here. Look at that.
Funny, isn't it?

1021
00:57:21,647 --> 00:57:23,314
"Jerry, Nellie, and Josie Cohan...

1022
00:57:23,524 --> 00:57:25,942
...the family of George M. Cohan,
the new Broadway sensation."

1023
00:57:26,151 --> 00:57:28,486
Hey, the kid's doing all right, isn't he?

1024
00:57:28,695 --> 00:57:30,238
JERRY:
Look at that.

1025
00:57:31,573 --> 00:57:34,492
Well, that's true.
He is the biggest thing on Broadway.

1026
00:57:34,701 --> 00:57:37,412
Yeah, I know, but it ain't right.
We'll build our own reputation.

1027
00:57:37,621 --> 00:57:39,705
We'll be billed as we should be:
The Three Cohans.

1028
00:57:39,915 --> 00:57:42,125
All right, no need to get excited.

1029
00:57:42,334 --> 00:57:44,210
Don't think I'm jealous
of Georgie's success...

1030
00:57:44,420 --> 00:57:45,795
...even though I am a better actor.

1031
00:57:46,004 --> 00:57:48,506
Of course you're not jealous.
Everybody knows that.

1032
00:57:48,715 --> 00:57:50,383
NELLIE:
Oh, there'll be no stopping George.

1033
00:57:50,592 --> 00:57:53,553
All he needs is a little more experience,
and he'll be a genius.

1034
00:57:53,762 --> 00:57:56,722
He mustn't know I'm better.
It might interfere with him becoming a genius.

1035
00:57:56,932 --> 00:58:00,435
Still, it does look a little funny:
George being the toast of Broadway...

1036
00:58:00,644 --> 00:58:02,895
...and you folks gathering
a few crumbs in the tank towns.

1037
00:58:03,105 --> 00:58:05,940
- Is either of you fellas Jerry Cohan?
JERRY: I am.

1038
00:58:06,150 --> 00:58:08,109
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

1039
00:58:13,240 --> 00:58:15,199
[THUNDER CRASHING]

1040
00:58:15,409 --> 00:58:16,576
It's from George.

1041
00:58:18,162 --> 00:58:21,330
"Impossible to find three clever actors
named Cohan...

1042
00:58:21,540 --> 00:58:23,875
...for my new show
anywhere in New York.

1043
00:58:24,084 --> 00:58:25,918
Return immediately for rehearsals."

1044
00:58:26,795 --> 00:58:29,380
- What'd I tell you?
- The four of us back together again...

1045
00:58:29,590 --> 00:58:31,299
...and on Broadway!

1046
00:58:31,508 --> 00:58:34,469
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING MERRY MUSIC]

1047
00:58:36,805 --> 00:58:39,140
MEN [SINGING]:
Oh, you wonderful girl

1048
00:58:39,349 --> 00:58:42,560
What a wonderful girl you are

1049
00:58:42,769 --> 00:58:45,521
You made the world appear to me

1050
00:58:45,731 --> 00:58:48,566
Near to me, dear to me

1051
00:58:48,775 --> 00:58:51,611
WOMEN:
Blue skies, gray skies

1052
00:58:51,820 --> 00:58:54,530
Main Street or Broadway skies

1053
00:58:54,740 --> 00:58:57,825
ALL:
Under December or May skies

1054
00:58:58,035 --> 00:59:00,661
I'll be true to you

1055
00:59:00,871 --> 00:59:03,247
Everybody's going to the barber's ball

1056
00:59:03,457 --> 00:59:05,458
There ain't a-gonna be any sleep at all

1057
00:59:05,667 --> 00:59:08,044
Until the stars are gone
Until the break of dawn

1058
00:59:08,253 --> 00:59:11,130
We're going to dance
At the barber's ball

1059
00:59:13,050 --> 00:59:15,343
[PLAYING PIANO
WHILE MARY VOCALIZES]

1060
00:59:15,552 --> 00:59:17,428
Even in the kitchen,
you sound like a tetrazzini.

1061
00:59:17,638 --> 00:59:20,264
Heh. In Buffalo,
they say I have a nice little voice.

1062
00:59:20,474 --> 00:59:24,185
Yeah. A lot they know in Buffalo.
In Buffalo they thought I was an old man.

1063
00:59:25,687 --> 00:59:27,688
Well, how do you like your part so far?

1064
00:59:27,898 --> 00:59:29,899
Oh, I like it.
I like it because it's small.

1065
00:59:30,108 --> 00:59:31,776
I'd be afraid to try anything bigger.

1066
00:59:31,985 --> 00:59:34,737
You've got something on the leading lady.
You got the best song.

1067
00:59:34,947 --> 00:59:37,365
Here it is. It's finished. Come on.

1068
00:59:37,574 --> 00:59:39,492
- What about the lyrics?
- Gonna give it to you now.

1069
00:59:39,701 --> 00:59:41,369
Sit down and give me a pickup.

1070
00:59:44,289 --> 00:59:46,249
[PLAYING GENTLE MELODY]

1071
00:59:47,876 --> 00:59:50,586
My mother's name was Mary.

1072
00:59:51,004 --> 00:59:53,381
She was so good and true.

1073
00:59:54,258 --> 00:59:56,884
Because her name was Mary...

1074
00:59:57,886 --> 01:00:00,429
...she called me Mary too.

1075
01:00:02,224 --> 01:00:05,142
She wasn't gay or airy...

1076
01:00:05,352 --> 01:00:07,728
...but plain as she could be.

1077
01:00:08,564 --> 01:00:12,149
I'd hate to meet a Mary...

1078
01:00:12,651 --> 01:00:16,112
...who called herself Marie.

1079
01:00:17,656 --> 01:00:19,824
For it is Mary...

1080
01:00:20,534 --> 01:00:22,493
...Mary...

1081
01:00:22,703 --> 01:00:25,871
...plain as any name can be.

1082
01:00:26,623 --> 01:00:28,583
But with propriety...

1083
01:00:28,792 --> 01:00:30,876
...society...

1084
01:00:31,086 --> 01:00:35,548
...will say, "Hm-hm. Marie."

1085
01:00:35,757 --> 01:00:38,050
But it was Mary...

1086
01:00:38,260 --> 01:00:40,136
...Mary...

1087
01:00:40,345 --> 01:00:43,723
...long before the fashions came.

1088
01:00:44,266 --> 01:00:46,767
And there is something there...

1089
01:00:46,977 --> 01:00:50,605
...that sounds so square...

1090
01:00:50,814 --> 01:00:55,276
...it's a grand old name.

1091
01:00:56,403 --> 01:00:59,405
[SINGING]
For it is Mary

1092
01:00:59,615 --> 01:01:01,449
Mary

1093
01:01:01,658 --> 01:01:05,453
Plain as any name can be

1094
01:01:05,662 --> 01:01:08,080
BOTH:
But with propriety

1095
01:01:08,290 --> 01:01:14,003
Society will say, "Marie"

1096
01:01:14,212 --> 01:01:17,089
But it was Mary

1097
01:01:17,299 --> 01:01:18,966
Mary

1098
01:01:19,176 --> 01:01:22,678
Long before the fashions came

1099
01:01:22,888 --> 01:01:25,890
And there is something there

1100
01:01:26,099 --> 01:01:29,477
That sounds so square

1101
01:01:29,686 --> 01:01:35,983
It's a grand old name

1102
01:01:36,193 --> 01:01:38,152
Mm-hm. Yeah.

1103
01:01:39,196 --> 01:01:42,448
Gee, I never cared much for my name before.
It was kind of common.

1104
01:01:42,658 --> 01:01:45,159
Gee, there are millions of Marys around,
but now...

1105
01:01:45,369 --> 01:01:47,244
But I didn't write it
for the millions of Marys.

1106
01:01:47,454 --> 01:01:50,289
I wrote it for one particular,
very special Mary.

1107
01:01:50,499 --> 01:01:53,125
Gee, it's a wonderful feeling having
your name written to music.

1108
01:01:53,335 --> 01:01:56,253
- And not bad music, either, huh?
- Nope, it isn't.

1109
01:01:56,463 --> 01:01:58,464
But how will everybody know
that I'm the Mary?

1110
01:01:58,674 --> 01:02:01,634
I want to make sure that everybody knows
it was written for me.

1111
01:02:01,843 --> 01:02:03,260
They'll know, all right.

1112
01:02:03,470 --> 01:02:07,098
When they look at you singing that song
and then look at me looking at you...

1113
01:02:07,307 --> 01:02:09,517
- ...they'll know.
- Oh, George.

1114
01:02:09,726 --> 01:02:11,185
Take that up an octave.

1115
01:02:11,395 --> 01:02:13,354
- George.
- Better.

1116
01:02:14,398 --> 01:02:16,982
Excuse me for butting in.
I've been looking all over town for you.

1117
01:02:17,192 --> 01:02:19,151
Strange that I should find you here.
Hello, Mary.

1118
01:02:19,361 --> 01:02:22,571
Mr. Harris, George has just written
a new song for me to sing in his show.

1119
01:02:22,781 --> 01:02:25,366
- Think I can do it?
- Of course. You've got a nice little voice.

1120
01:02:25,575 --> 01:02:27,702
That is not a little voice,
and you need an ear trumpet.

1121
01:02:27,911 --> 01:02:30,871
Come on, we've gotta get off to the Lyceum.
We've got to see Fay Templeton.

1122
01:02:31,039 --> 01:02:33,749
- What does she want to see us about?
- She doesn't. We want to see her.

1123
01:02:33,959 --> 01:02:36,335
You need a leading lady.
You've got your ingenue.

1124
01:02:36,545 --> 01:02:38,838
- George.
- Hmm, Fay Templeton. That's not bad.

1125
01:02:39,047 --> 01:02:41,382
She can do four years for us.

1126
01:02:41,591 --> 01:02:43,050
- Think she'll take it?
- I don't know.

1127
01:02:43,260 --> 01:02:45,886
- At least you can get her autograph.
GEORGE: Or for her to get mine.

1128
01:02:46,096 --> 01:02:47,888
MARY:
Bring her back to supper after the show.

1129
01:02:48,098 --> 01:02:50,057
I will if she's still speaking to us.

1130
01:03:01,278 --> 01:03:03,529
[WOMAN AND SAM
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

1131
01:03:03,739 --> 01:03:06,574
WOMAN:
Would you like to buy it? Thank you.

1132
01:03:06,783 --> 01:03:09,076
SAM: There's one thing in our favor.
Erlanger's on our side.

1133
01:03:09,286 --> 01:03:12,705
- He's got influence with Miss Templeton.
- You talk to him, and I'll tackle Templeton.

1134
01:03:12,914 --> 01:03:14,707
You don't tackle a star
like Miss Templeton.

1135
01:03:14,916 --> 01:03:19,170
- You approach her and very tactfully too.
- Well, if it's tact that does it, it's done.

1136
01:03:21,089 --> 01:03:24,216
If you get me in to see Miss Templeton,
I'll get you two passes to my next show.

1137
01:03:24,426 --> 01:03:26,927
Dan, look. Dietz.
Looks naked without Goff.

1138
01:03:27,137 --> 01:03:29,138
Heh. Yeah.
Where's Miss Templeton's dressing room?

1139
01:03:29,347 --> 01:03:31,265
MAN: Upstairs.
- I tell you what I'm going to do.

1140
01:03:31,475 --> 01:03:33,934
I'm gonna see to it
that Miss Templeton gets your flowers.

1141
01:03:34,144 --> 01:03:36,270
My respects to Mrs. Dietz.

1142
01:03:37,022 --> 01:03:39,273
[SLURRING]
Now, that was a very sweet gesture.

1143
01:03:39,483 --> 01:03:41,942
But you've got to remember, Fay,
we're having a tough time...

1144
01:03:42,152 --> 01:03:43,527
...lining up a vehicle for you.

1145
01:03:43,737 --> 01:03:45,905
Now, you should listen to this man.

1146
01:03:46,114 --> 01:03:48,199
- He's just written a big hit.
- One hit.

1147
01:03:48,408 --> 01:03:50,451
He may be a flash in the pan
for all we know.

1148
01:03:50,660 --> 01:03:52,453
And I heard about Little Johnny Jones.

1149
01:03:52,662 --> 01:03:54,246
And I read the critics... Pfft.

1150
01:03:54,456 --> 01:03:56,916
-- of all the loud, vulgar flag-waving.

1151
01:03:57,125 --> 01:04:00,419
Well, it was a wow.
I haven't laughed so much in years.

1152
01:04:00,629 --> 01:04:02,004
The fellow's got the golden touch.

1153
01:04:02,214 --> 01:04:04,590
Maybe so, but not for me, Mr. Erlanger.

1154
01:04:04,800 --> 01:04:07,301
What I want is a quiet,
dignified musical play.

1155
01:04:07,511 --> 01:04:09,637
I want to perform in a theater,
not a boiler factory.

1156
01:04:09,846 --> 01:04:10,805
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

1157
01:04:11,014 --> 01:04:12,431
ERLANGER:
Come in.

1158
01:04:12,641 --> 01:04:15,059
- Hello, Harris. How are you, Cohan?
- Hello, Abe.

1159
01:04:15,268 --> 01:04:17,102
Everything's all right. You'll see.

1160
01:04:17,312 --> 01:04:21,398
Oh, uh, Fay,
uh, may I present Mr. Harris.

1161
01:04:21,608 --> 01:04:24,318
- How do you do?
- And, uh, Fay, this is Mr. Cohan.

1162
01:04:24,528 --> 01:04:26,737
- George M. Cohan.
- How do you do?

1163
01:04:26,947 --> 01:04:30,241
We were just talking about you, George.
Miss Templeton's never seen your work.

1164
01:04:30,450 --> 01:04:32,493
Hmm. Been sick or in Europe?

1165
01:04:33,453 --> 01:04:35,204
[ERLANGER CHUCKLES]

1166
01:04:35,413 --> 01:04:39,083
No. I've been right here
on this stage for two years.

1167
01:04:39,292 --> 01:04:40,376
Oh, buried.

1168
01:04:40,585 --> 01:04:43,337
Oh, uh, don't misunderstand me,
Miss Templeton. I, uh...

1169
01:04:43,547 --> 01:04:45,548
Well, I've never been
at a loss for words before...

1170
01:04:45,757 --> 01:04:49,552
...but right now standing here
in your presence, why, I hardly...

1171
01:04:49,761 --> 01:04:52,471
Well, I'd prefer to have
these flowers speak for me.

1172
01:04:52,681 --> 01:04:55,850
- Why, Mr. Cohan, how sweet of you.
- Oh, it was nothing at all.

1173
01:04:56,059 --> 01:04:58,477
Excuse me for breaking in on you like this,
Miss Templeton...

1174
01:04:58,687 --> 01:05:01,689
...but I would like to present
my own flowers my own way.

1175
01:05:01,898 --> 01:05:04,817
- But, Mr. Cohan, I thought... Is he?
- Drunk.

1176
01:05:05,026 --> 01:05:08,779
May I have the honor of supping with you
at Rex's tonight after the show...

1177
01:05:08,989 --> 01:05:10,781
...and drinking champagne
out of your...

1178
01:05:10,991 --> 01:05:12,908
- Pardon me. --slipper?
SAM: Excuse me, Mr. Dietz.

1179
01:05:13,118 --> 01:05:16,203
Haven't you forgotten that your junior partner,
Goff, does all the drinking?

1180
01:05:16,413 --> 01:05:19,164
Yes, but on special occasions,
I take over...

1181
01:05:19,374 --> 01:05:21,083
May I put these in water for you?

1182
01:05:21,293 --> 01:05:24,128
- Well, really, I...
ERLANGER: I never saw Dietz drunk before.

1183
01:05:24,337 --> 01:05:26,672
Heh-heh.
Well, uh, shall we get down to business?

1184
01:05:26,882 --> 01:05:27,965
If you like, Abe.

1185
01:05:28,174 --> 01:05:30,092
Well, George,
how would you like to do a play...

1186
01:05:30,302 --> 01:05:31,969
...with one of the biggest stars
in America?

1187
01:05:32,178 --> 01:05:34,096
- What do you think I've been doing?
- Heh. Yes.

1188
01:05:34,306 --> 01:05:37,182
You see what I mean, Fay?
Heh-heh. Isn't he a card?

1189
01:05:37,392 --> 01:05:38,893
Positively a riot.

1190
01:05:39,102 --> 01:05:42,229
Yes, well, George,
what's your new story like?

1191
01:05:42,439 --> 01:05:45,399
That is, I mean,
can you write a play without a flag?

1192
01:05:45,609 --> 01:05:48,444
Miss Templeton, I can write a play
without anything except a pencil.

1193
01:05:48,653 --> 01:05:52,031
- Laugh. Now, look...
- There's really no use discussing anything.

1194
01:05:52,240 --> 01:05:56,076
I would never please the sort of people
who revel in your antics and fireworks.

1195
01:05:56,286 --> 01:05:57,995
Oh, you're just being modest,
Miss Templeton.

1196
01:05:58,204 --> 01:06:01,415
If you'd let yourself go, you'd be just as noisy
and entertaining as the rest of us.

1197
01:06:01,625 --> 01:06:03,042
You might even have fun yourself.

1198
01:06:03,251 --> 01:06:05,502
Abe, isn't it about time
for the curtain to go up?

1199
01:06:05,712 --> 01:06:08,422
Look, if you haven't got time now,
maybe a few minutes after the show.

1200
01:06:08,632 --> 01:06:11,175
I'm sorry. After the show
I'm going home to New Rochelle.

1201
01:06:11,384 --> 01:06:12,885
It's only 45 minutes from here...

1202
01:06:13,094 --> 01:06:15,888
...but it's like a thousand miles
from all the noisy, neurotic people...

1203
01:06:16,097 --> 01:06:18,015
...one has to associate with
in our profession.

1204
01:06:18,224 --> 01:06:19,892
GEORGE:
Now, Miss Templeton, you can't...

1205
01:06:20,101 --> 01:06:23,729
ERLANGER: Fay, I warned you.
- That tact of yours. That wonderful tact.

1206
01:06:23,939 --> 01:06:25,439
[DOOR CLOSES]

1207
01:06:28,360 --> 01:06:30,069
What are you thinking about?

1208
01:06:32,656 --> 01:06:34,615
[FAY SINGING FINAL NOTES]

1209
01:06:37,118 --> 01:06:39,078
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

1210
01:06:40,163 --> 01:06:42,247
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

1211
01:06:42,958 --> 01:06:44,541
Well, have you thought it over, Fay?

1212
01:06:44,751 --> 01:06:46,502
I'm not interested in Mr. Cohan
or his plays.

1213
01:06:46,711 --> 01:06:48,379
Now you're making a great mistake, Fay.

1214
01:06:48,588 --> 01:06:51,590
He's the most original thing
that ever hit Broadway. You know why?

1215
01:06:51,800 --> 01:06:54,969
Because he's the whole darn country
squeezed into one pair of pants.

1216
01:06:55,178 --> 01:06:58,055
His writing, his song,
why, even his walk and his talk...

1217
01:06:58,264 --> 01:07:00,724
...they all touch something
way down here in people.

1218
01:07:00,934 --> 01:07:04,019
Now, don't ask me why it is, but it happens
every time the curtain goes up.

1219
01:07:04,229 --> 01:07:05,479
It's pure magic.

1220
01:07:05,689 --> 01:07:08,065
I'm bored by magic. I know his formula.

1221
01:07:08,274 --> 01:07:11,151
A fresh, young sprout gets rich
between 8:30 and 11 p.m.

1222
01:07:11,361 --> 01:07:12,987
Yes, that's just it, Fay.

1223
01:07:13,196 --> 01:07:15,531
George M. Cohan has invented
the success story.

1224
01:07:15,740 --> 01:07:19,368
And every American loves it because
it happens to be his own private dream.

1225
01:07:19,577 --> 01:07:21,954
He's found the mainspring
in the antique clock.

1226
01:07:22,163 --> 01:07:24,123
Ambition, pride, patriotism.

1227
01:07:24,332 --> 01:07:26,500
That's why they call him
the Yankee Doodle boy.

1228
01:07:26,710 --> 01:07:29,586
Now, if you'll take a tip from me, Fay,
you'll do just what I'm doing.

1229
01:07:29,796 --> 01:07:32,297
You'll hitch your wagon
to his star right now.

1230
01:07:32,507 --> 01:07:35,134
Abe, I've got to change
for the second act.

1231
01:07:36,720 --> 01:07:38,554
Now, Fay, don't make up
your mind too quickly.

1232
01:07:38,763 --> 01:07:40,264
Take a little time. Think it over.

1233
01:07:40,473 --> 01:07:41,598
Who's locked my door?

1234
01:07:41,808 --> 01:07:43,142
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

1235
01:07:43,351 --> 01:07:45,686
SAM: Who is it?
FAY: What's going on here?

1236
01:07:45,895 --> 01:07:47,855
He'll be through in a minute.

1237
01:07:48,064 --> 01:07:51,233
Excuse me. I beg your pardon.
I didn't realize who you were. Come in.

1238
01:07:51,443 --> 01:07:53,027
- May I?
- Why, of course.

1239
01:07:53,236 --> 01:07:54,695
What does this mean?

1240
01:07:54,904 --> 01:07:56,780
Would you mind telling me
why you're still here?

1241
01:07:56,990 --> 01:07:58,699
Well, here it is,
ready and dedicated to you.

1242
01:07:58,908 --> 01:08:00,909
- What?
- Well, uh, when you made that exit speech...

1243
01:08:01,119 --> 01:08:02,745
...you said you lived
only 45 minutes away.

1244
01:08:02,954 --> 01:08:05,581
That struck me as being a perfect title
for a show and for a song.

1245
01:08:05,790 --> 01:08:08,125
During the first act,
you've written this new song?

1246
01:08:08,334 --> 01:08:09,877
Strange surrounding.
It took me longer.

1247
01:08:10,086 --> 01:08:12,171
He's worked so hard.
The least you could do is hear it.

1248
01:08:12,380 --> 01:08:15,716
- Yeah, it'll only take a minute, won't it?
- Depends on the encores. Heh.

1249
01:08:15,925 --> 01:08:18,802
Well, you certainly are persistent.
All right, go ahead.

1250
01:08:19,763 --> 01:08:21,346
- Mind if I change?
SAM: Oh, thank you.

1251
01:08:21,556 --> 01:08:24,725
That's wonderful of you. Thank you very,
very much. Go ahead, George. Play it.

1252
01:08:26,102 --> 01:08:28,062
[PLAYING PIANO]

1253
01:08:29,147 --> 01:08:32,900
[SINGING]
Only 45 minutes from Broadway

1254
01:08:33,109 --> 01:08:35,903
Think of the changes it brings

1255
01:08:36,112 --> 01:08:39,281
For the short time it takes
What a difference it makes

1256
01:08:39,491 --> 01:08:42,826
In the ways of the people and things

1257
01:08:43,036 --> 01:08:46,205
Oh, what a fine bunch of Reubens

1258
01:08:46,414 --> 01:08:49,208
Oh, what a jay atmosphere

1259
01:08:49,417 --> 01:08:52,461
They have whiskers like hay
And imagine Broadway

1260
01:08:52,670 --> 01:08:55,214
Only 45 minutes from here

1261
01:08:56,049 --> 01:08:58,092
Only 45 minutes

1262
01:08:58,301 --> 01:09:01,303
That's good. It's rather different.

1263
01:09:01,513 --> 01:09:03,055
- You liked it, Miss Templeton?
FAY: Ah!

1264
01:09:03,264 --> 01:09:05,557
Excuse me.
That's only a chorus number.

1265
01:09:05,767 --> 01:09:07,976
He's got one number called "Mary"
that's perfect for you.

1266
01:09:08,186 --> 01:09:09,937
- She doesn't sing that.
- She is gonna sing it.

1267
01:09:10,146 --> 01:09:11,313
- No, no, no.
- Shut up.

1268
01:09:11,523 --> 01:09:13,107
It's the best thing he's ever done.

1269
01:09:14,818 --> 01:09:16,610
"Mary," hmm?

1270
01:09:17,070 --> 01:09:18,445
This looks very interesting.

1271
01:09:18,655 --> 01:09:20,489
GEORGE:
It's only a so-so number.

1272
01:09:20,698 --> 01:09:22,616
If it's as good
as "45 Minutes from Broadway"...

1273
01:09:22,826 --> 01:09:25,953
- Well, it isn't, and besides, you...
- What do you want to do, spoil everything?

1274
01:09:26,162 --> 01:09:28,664
- I can't let her have that.
- What difference does it make?

1275
01:09:28,873 --> 01:09:30,958
- She's gonna sing it. She will.
- But she can't sing it.

1276
01:09:31,167 --> 01:09:33,710
With Abe's money and your brains,
we'll be able to make a million.

1277
01:09:33,920 --> 01:09:35,420
SAM:
Shh!

1278
01:09:35,630 --> 01:09:37,923
[HUMMING WHILE PLAYING PIANO]

1279
01:09:54,357 --> 01:09:57,442
[SINGING]
For it is Mary

1280
01:09:57,652 --> 01:09:59,653
Mary

1281
01:09:59,863 --> 01:10:01,822
[MARY VOCALIZING AND HUMMING]

1282
01:10:07,245 --> 01:10:11,248
Society will say

1283
01:10:11,457 --> 01:10:13,959
"Marie"

1284
01:10:14,169 --> 01:10:17,045
But it was Mary

1285
01:10:17,255 --> 01:10:19,631
Mary

1286
01:10:19,841 --> 01:10:23,927
Long before the fashions came

1287
01:10:24,512 --> 01:10:26,471
[DOOR BUZZES]

1288
01:10:26,681 --> 01:10:28,140
Come in.

1289
01:10:29,225 --> 01:10:31,393
Oh! A little early for Christmas, isn't it?

1290
01:10:31,603 --> 01:10:35,022
Well, I was just passing the flowers,
and they threw in the candy.

1291
01:10:35,231 --> 01:10:37,149
George, I'm sure our song will live forever.

1292
01:10:37,358 --> 01:10:40,903
I've been playing it ever since you left,
and the neighbors haven't complained once.

1293
01:10:41,112 --> 01:10:42,613
What happened with Fay Templeton?

1294
01:10:42,822 --> 01:10:45,574
Oh, she's dying to play the part.
But I haven't made up my mind yet.

1295
01:10:45,783 --> 01:10:47,117
Mmm. Ham or bacon?

1296
01:10:47,327 --> 01:10:49,536
- Bacon.
- Good. Ham makes me self-conscious.

1297
01:10:49,746 --> 01:10:51,997
You're hesitating
about having Fay Templeton in your show?

1298
01:10:52,207 --> 01:10:55,334
You know how those big stars are.
Temperamental and hard to get along with.

1299
01:10:55,543 --> 01:10:57,085
Asking impossible terms
and conditions.

1300
01:10:57,295 --> 01:10:59,504
- I'll take my coffee black.
- You ought to give in to her.

1301
01:10:59,714 --> 01:11:02,466
But, darling,
no matter what she asks?

1302
01:11:02,675 --> 01:11:06,261
- No matter what she asks.
- Why are you so concerned for Templeton?

1303
01:11:06,471 --> 01:11:09,348
Oh, I don't care for Templeton.
I'm looking out for you.

1304
01:11:09,557 --> 01:11:13,268
Think what it means for you to have
a star like Templeton in your show.

1305
01:11:13,478 --> 01:11:16,897
Mm-hm. Always worried about me,
aren't you? Ever think about yourself?

1306
01:11:18,107 --> 01:11:20,400
Not much lately. Haven't had time.

1307
01:11:20,610 --> 01:11:22,236
The minute I saw you
without your beard...

1308
01:11:22,445 --> 01:11:24,738
...I knew here was a little boy
who needed looking after...

1309
01:11:24,948 --> 01:11:27,741
- ...so I gave myself the job.
- Mm-hm.

1310
01:11:27,951 --> 01:11:31,536
There are a lot of singers, you know,
but very few really good looker-afters.

1311
01:11:31,746 --> 01:11:33,497
GEORGE:
Mm-hm.

1312
01:11:33,706 --> 01:11:37,668
Darling, how would you like
a lifetime job of looking after?

1313
01:11:37,877 --> 01:11:39,753
Leading lady, run of the play...

1314
01:11:39,963 --> 01:11:42,047
...maybe a few heartaches
after the curtain goes up...

1315
01:11:42,257 --> 01:11:44,383
...but I can guarantee you some laughs.

1316
01:11:44,592 --> 01:11:46,260
How does it sound?

1317
01:11:46,928 --> 01:11:49,263
I think I might like it, Mr. Cohan.

1318
01:11:49,472 --> 01:11:52,015
Could I, uh, see some of the script?

1319
01:11:52,225 --> 01:11:53,684
Mm-hm.

1320
01:11:56,646 --> 01:11:58,230
Hmm.

1321
01:11:58,439 --> 01:12:00,607
Not bad for a first reading.

1322
01:12:03,403 --> 01:12:04,945
The coffee's boiling over.

1323
01:12:06,281 --> 01:12:08,115
Darling, there's something
I forgot to tell you.

1324
01:12:08,324 --> 01:12:11,743
- Yes, dear?
- Uh, I gave your song to Templeton tonight.

1325
01:12:11,953 --> 01:12:12,911
MARY:
Mm-hm.

1326
01:12:14,122 --> 01:12:17,708
Darling, did you hear me? I, uh...

1327
01:12:17,917 --> 01:12:20,085
I gave your song
to Fay Templeton tonight.

1328
01:12:20,295 --> 01:12:25,090
Yes, I know. I knew you did, dear,
when you brought the candy and flowers.

1329
01:12:31,264 --> 01:12:34,224
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING
LUSH ARRANGEMENT]

1330
01:12:51,617 --> 01:12:55,412
[SINGING]
My mother's name was Mary

1331
01:12:55,621 --> 01:12:59,374
She was so good and true

1332
01:12:59,584 --> 01:13:03,295
Because her name was Mary

1333
01:13:03,504 --> 01:13:08,300
She calls me Mary too

1334
01:13:08,509 --> 01:13:12,304
She wasn't gay or airy

1335
01:13:12,513 --> 01:13:17,142
But plain as she could be

1336
01:13:17,352 --> 01:13:21,563
I'd hate to meet a Mary

1337
01:13:21,773 --> 01:13:28,111
Who calls herself Marie

1338
01:13:28,321 --> 01:13:31,698
For it was Mary

1339
01:13:31,908 --> 01:13:34,034
Mary

1340
01:13:34,243 --> 01:13:37,829
Plain as any name can be

1341
01:13:38,039 --> 01:13:40,499
But with propriety

1342
01:13:40,708 --> 01:13:46,880
Society will say, "Marie"

1343
01:13:47,090 --> 01:13:49,883
For it was Mary

1344
01:13:50,093 --> 01:13:52,094
Mary

1345
01:13:52,303 --> 01:13:56,014
Long before the fashions came

1346
01:13:56,224 --> 01:13:59,726
And there is something there

1347
01:13:59,936 --> 01:14:03,522
That sounds so square

1348
01:14:03,731 --> 01:14:07,484
It's a wonderful song, George,
best you've ever done. It’ll live for years.

1349
01:14:07,693 --> 01:14:11,113
Thanks, Sam.
But I still think Mary should have sung it.

1350
01:14:11,322 --> 01:14:15,992
Oh, that's all right.
Fay has the song, but I have the author.

1351
01:14:18,913 --> 01:14:22,457
And there is something there

1352
01:14:22,667 --> 01:14:27,379
That sounds so square

1353
01:14:27,588 --> 01:14:29,714
It's a grand

1354
01:14:29,924 --> 01:14:32,092
Old

1355
01:14:32,301 --> 01:14:35,387
Name

1356
01:14:35,596 --> 01:14:37,139
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

1357
01:14:37,348 --> 01:14:41,935
Only 45 minutes from Broadway

1358
01:14:42,145 --> 01:14:45,272
Think of the changes it brings

1359
01:14:45,982 --> 01:14:51,111
For the short time it takes
What a difference it makes

1360
01:14:51,320 --> 01:14:55,115
ALL:
In the ways of the people and things

1361
01:14:55,324 --> 01:14:57,951
Oh, and things

1362
01:14:58,161 --> 01:15:01,913
Oh, what a fine bunch of Reubens

1363
01:15:02,123 --> 01:15:05,709
Oh, what a jay atmosphere

1364
01:15:05,918 --> 01:15:07,752
They have whiskers like hay

1365
01:15:07,962 --> 01:15:13,758
And imagine Broadway
Only 45 minutes from here

1366
01:15:15,094 --> 01:15:17,053
[ALL WHISTLING]

1367
01:15:22,185 --> 01:15:24,144
[MEN VOCALIZING]

1368
01:15:31,027 --> 01:15:34,821
It's awfully nice of all you boys
To see me to the train

1369
01:15:35,031 --> 01:15:38,533
CHORUS:
So long, Mary

1370
01:15:38,743 --> 01:15:42,120
I didn't think you'd care
If you should never see me again

1371
01:15:42,330 --> 01:15:45,540
CHORUS:
You're wrong, Mary

1372
01:15:45,750 --> 01:15:49,461
This reminds me of my family

1373
01:15:49,670 --> 01:15:53,131
On the day I left Schenectady

1374
01:15:53,341 --> 01:15:56,801
To the depot
Then they came with me

1375
01:15:57,011 --> 01:16:02,933
I seem to hear them say

1376
01:16:03,142 --> 01:16:04,893
[MEN VOCALIZING]

1377
01:16:05,102 --> 01:16:09,189
"So long, Mary"

1378
01:16:09,398 --> 01:16:13,151
CHORUS:
Mary, we will miss you so

1379
01:16:13,361 --> 01:16:16,947
"So long, Mary"

1380
01:16:17,156 --> 01:16:20,367
CHORUS:
How we hate to see you go

1381
01:16:20,576 --> 01:16:24,496
"And we'll all be longing for you, Mary

1382
01:16:24,705 --> 01:16:28,083
While you roam"

1383
01:16:28,292 --> 01:16:31,836
ALL:
So long, Mary

1384
01:16:32,046 --> 01:16:35,590
Don't forget to come back home

1385
01:16:35,800 --> 01:16:39,094
So long, Mary

1386
