01:25:09,396 --> 01:25:13,066
Flag

1528
01:25:13,275 --> 01:25:14,734
[ALL CHEERING]

1529
01:25:31,418 --> 01:25:33,628
[SINGING]
Like the wandering minstrel

1530
01:25:33,837 --> 01:25:37,840
I have slouched along the way

1531
01:25:38,050 --> 01:25:41,344
Wandering day by day

1532
01:25:41,553 --> 01:25:44,889
No selection of direction

1533
01:25:45,099 --> 01:25:48,226
Till I heard a lovely voice

1534
01:25:48,435 --> 01:25:51,979
Which seemed to softly say

1535
01:25:52,189 --> 01:25:53,689
Come along with me

1536
01:25:53,899 --> 01:25:57,693
Come along with me away

1537
01:26:01,657 --> 01:26:03,574
May I have your autograph,
Mr. Cohan?

1538
01:26:03,784 --> 01:26:06,869
To what do you attribute
your continued success, Mr. Cohan?

1539
01:26:07,037 --> 01:26:10,248
Oh, I'm an ordinary guy who knows
what ordinary guys like to see.

1540
01:26:10,457 --> 01:26:12,416
[CROWD CHEERING]

1541
01:26:16,547 --> 01:26:19,257
Front row center,
the greatest show on earth, the people.

1542
01:26:19,466 --> 01:26:21,342
To the people. God bless them.

1543
01:26:27,099 --> 01:26:28,474
NELLIE:
Here, chick, chick, chick.

1544
01:26:28,684 --> 01:26:31,185
- Here, chick, chick, chick.
JOSIE: Heh.

1545
01:26:31,395 --> 01:26:34,355
Oh, it's such fun, Mother,
having cows and chickens.

1546
01:26:34,565 --> 01:26:36,357
And everything's running so smoothly.

1547
01:26:36,567 --> 01:26:38,442
Well, it's always been a dream of ours, Mary.

1548
01:26:38,652 --> 01:26:42,113
We kept hoping for 20 years
that it might come true someday.

1549
01:26:42,322 --> 01:26:45,616
Imagine knowing how to feed chickens
or how much to feed them.

1550
01:26:45,826 --> 01:26:47,577
And you're a farmer only three weeks.

1551
01:26:47,786 --> 01:26:50,163
Jerry and I have seen
a lot of chickens in train windows...

1552
01:26:50,372 --> 01:26:52,456
...and we always wanted
to raise some of our own.

1553
01:26:52,666 --> 01:26:55,459
You know, watch them hatch
and feed them and eat them.

1554
01:26:55,669 --> 01:26:58,588
If we only could. They're so pretty.

1555
01:26:59,631 --> 01:27:00,840
[GEORGE WHISTLING]

1556
01:27:01,049 --> 01:27:02,466
- Georgie?
- Yeah?

1557
01:27:02,676 --> 01:27:05,845
- What'd you get Dad for his birthday?
- Oh, nothing much. Just a smoking jacket.

1558
01:27:06,054 --> 01:27:08,097
Is it bright? Lots of color?
I mean, will he like it?

1559
01:27:08,307 --> 01:27:10,308
Well, it's silk and very red
and very yellow.

1560
01:27:10,517 --> 01:27:13,352
That'll do it.
Look what I got him, Georgie.

1561
01:27:13,937 --> 01:27:16,856
Well, now, there's a present.
That must have set you back a few.

1562
01:27:17,065 --> 01:27:18,232
Dad needed a new watch.

1563
01:27:18,442 --> 01:27:21,194
His old one's so loud,
you can hear it right through his coat.

1564
01:27:22,863 --> 01:27:24,030
[GEORGE WHISTLES]

1565
01:27:24,239 --> 01:27:26,699
My future husband helped me pick it out.

1566
01:27:28,994 --> 01:27:29,952
Your future what?

1567
01:27:31,330 --> 01:27:34,665
Husband. We're getting married
as soon as Fred's road tour is over.

1568
01:27:36,460 --> 01:27:37,501
Well...

1569
01:27:39,421 --> 01:27:40,588
GEORGE:
Hm.

1570
01:27:46,637 --> 01:27:47,845
Hm.

1571
01:27:53,685 --> 01:27:55,770
Little Josie's gonna get married, huh?

1572
01:27:56,688 --> 01:27:58,397
Oh, it doesn't seem that long ago...

1573
01:27:58,607 --> 01:28:00,066
Hmm.

1574
01:28:01,151 --> 01:28:03,194
What happens to The Four Cohans?

1575
01:28:03,403 --> 01:28:05,988
Oh, just a simple case of subtraction.

1576
01:28:06,198 --> 01:28:08,741
You know, one from four leaves three.

1577
01:28:09,284 --> 01:28:11,661
- Three Cohans.
- Mm-mm.

1578
01:28:11,870 --> 01:28:13,537
That's only arithmetic.

1579
01:28:13,747 --> 01:28:16,499
One Cohan from four Cohans
leaves nothing.

1580
01:28:17,376 --> 01:28:18,834
Mom and Pop know?

1581
01:28:19,044 --> 01:28:20,544
JOSIE:
Mm-hm.

1582
01:28:21,296 --> 01:28:24,006
Mom's been working
on the wedding dress for weeks.

1583
01:28:32,099 --> 01:28:34,016
What are you thinking about, Georgie?

1584
01:28:39,314 --> 01:28:42,984
I'm gonna write you the most terrific
wedding march ever put on paper.

1585
01:28:43,193 --> 01:28:45,278
It'll pack the pews.

1586
01:28:48,156 --> 01:28:52,493
Say, Dad, will you tell Josie
that there's no reason to break up the act?

1587
01:28:52,703 --> 01:28:54,912
The Four Cohans are as much
an institution as marriage is.

1588
01:28:55,122 --> 01:28:57,581
Oh, Georgie, no one knows that
any better than I do...

1589
01:28:57,791 --> 01:28:59,750
...but we want to settle down
and raise a family.

1590
01:28:59,960 --> 01:29:02,753
What's the matter? Can't he raise a family
and be a stage manager too?

1591
01:29:02,963 --> 01:29:04,547
- Hmm?
- George.

1592
01:29:04,756 --> 01:29:08,301
George, I'm afraid your mother and I
are breaking up the act before Josie is.

1593
01:29:14,433 --> 01:29:17,059
You hear that, Sam?
All three of them walking out on me.

1594
01:29:17,269 --> 01:29:18,978
There's been a 40-year run, remember?

1595
01:29:19,187 --> 01:29:21,355
We're giving you our two weeks' notice,
George. Heh.

1596
01:29:21,565 --> 01:29:24,734
All we'd like to do now is spend
the rest of our days here on this farm.

1597
01:29:24,943 --> 01:29:28,487
But you can't do that. You can't put
an actor out to grass. Fresh air kills him.

1598
01:29:28,697 --> 01:29:30,740
We've gained nearly 10 pounds apiece.

1599
01:29:30,949 --> 01:29:33,242
You can work it off.
The show is ready to go into rehearsal.

1600
01:29:33,452 --> 01:29:35,661
There are grand parts in it for both of you.

1601
01:29:35,871 --> 01:29:37,371
No, George, I...

1602
01:29:37,581 --> 01:29:39,415
We've had good times together.

1603
01:29:39,624 --> 01:29:43,044
And, well, new shows need new faces
and new feet to go with you.

1604
01:29:43,253 --> 01:29:45,921
From now on,
it's just you alone, son.

1605
01:29:49,092 --> 01:29:50,134
JERRY:
Well, what's this?

1606
01:29:50,344 --> 01:29:52,970
JOSIE: A surprise, Dad.
GEORGE: Happy birthday!

1607
01:29:53,180 --> 01:29:55,973
JERRY: For me? Heh.
GEORGE: You get your own birthday.

1608
01:29:56,183 --> 01:29:58,392
JERRY: Look at the size of that one.
JOSIE: Make a wish.

1609
01:29:58,602 --> 01:29:59,852
GEORGE: Make your wish.
- I have.

1610
01:30:00,062 --> 01:30:01,395
JOSIE:
A good one, Dad.

1611
01:30:02,439 --> 01:30:04,565
GEORGE:
Which one do you want to open first?

1612
01:30:04,775 --> 01:30:07,193
JOSIE: How about opening this one?
Let me help you.

1613
01:30:07,402 --> 01:30:10,946
- This one will match your suit, Dad.
JERRY: Somebody gave me that last year.

1614
01:30:11,156 --> 01:30:12,448
Well, it looks fine.

1615
01:30:12,657 --> 01:30:16,452
Had it made up on that old backdrop
you like so well, fireproofed and everything.

1616
01:30:16,661 --> 01:30:18,829
Oh, darling, that's a lovely watch. Heh.

1617
01:30:19,039 --> 01:30:20,164
I'm so glad you like it, Dad.

1618
01:30:20,374 --> 01:30:22,291
This is better
than being on next to closing.

1619
01:30:22,501 --> 01:30:24,418
The only trouble is it's three minutes fast.

1620
01:30:24,628 --> 01:30:28,005
Heh-heh. Dad, press the little button
on the side and see what happens.

1621
01:30:28,215 --> 01:30:30,132
[PLAYING "YANKEE DOODLE"]

1622
01:30:30,342 --> 01:30:31,509
[ALL LAUGH]

1623
01:30:31,718 --> 01:30:34,178
It plays one on one
and segues into "Dixie."

1624
01:30:34,388 --> 01:30:36,222
Here's some more ties
that you won't like, Jerry.

1625
01:30:36,431 --> 01:30:38,933
I'll have to open up a store, huh?
Heh-heh.

1626
01:30:39,768 --> 01:30:41,310
- Oh, uh...
- Here's a letter from George.

1627
01:30:41,520 --> 01:30:44,271
- Don't open that now...
- You haven't written me a letter in 20 years.

1628
01:30:44,481 --> 01:30:46,273
I'm gonna open it now,
and I'm gonna read it.

1629
01:30:46,483 --> 01:30:49,276
George, this isn't your party.
Sit down and let him read his letter.

1630
01:30:49,486 --> 01:30:51,445
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1631
01:30:58,036 --> 01:31:01,956
"Dear Dad, this is your 62nd birthday,
and God bless you.

1632
01:31:02,332 --> 01:31:06,293
Maybe I've never told you before,
but no son ever had a better dad...

1633
01:31:06,503 --> 01:31:08,587
...or one to be prouder of.

1634
01:31:08,797 --> 01:31:12,967
You and mother have always given me
more love and understanding...

1635
01:31:13,176 --> 01:31:14,802
...than I ever deserved.

1636
01:31:15,011 --> 01:31:19,473
And all the luck I've had is due
to the things you two have taught me.

1637
01:31:19,850 --> 01:31:23,352
Nothing I can do could ever repay the debt.

1638
01:31:26,314 --> 01:31:29,900
But here's a little present
for you and mother.

1639
01:31:30,110 --> 01:31:34,155
From this day on,
you and I are partners...

1640
01:31:34,364 --> 01:31:39,410
...in every theater and theatrical property
I possess...

1641
01:31:39,619 --> 01:31:40,786
...half and equal.

1642
01:31:42,289 --> 01:31:46,584
The Cohan Theater, the Astor, the Gaiety...

1643
01:31:46,793 --> 01:31:48,752
...and the Grand Opera House in Chicago...

1644
01:31:50,630 --> 01:31:53,591
...and all my plays and songs
as long as they...

1645
01:31:54,593 --> 01:31:57,011
...or you and I, live."

1646
01:32:00,682 --> 01:32:03,017
These are not my reading glasses.

1647
01:32:03,643 --> 01:32:06,854
Why didn't somebody give me
some reading glasses for my birthday?

1648
01:32:07,814 --> 01:32:09,482
"Wish you all my love...

1649
01:32:10,901 --> 01:32:13,611
...your son and partner, George."

1650
01:32:16,698 --> 01:32:19,783
Well, George, on behalf
of your mother and myself, I...

1651
01:32:19,993 --> 01:32:21,660
[NELLIE SOBBING]

1652
01:32:22,412 --> 01:32:24,079
There she goes stealing the scene again.

1653
01:32:24,289 --> 01:32:25,623
[ALL LAUGH]

1654
01:32:30,045 --> 01:32:31,504
GEORGE:
One success followed another...

1655
01:32:31,713 --> 01:32:33,547
...but there was one challenge
I hadn't met.

1656
01:32:33,757 --> 01:32:36,717
Critics kept saying that musicals
and cheap comedies were all I could write.

1657
01:32:36,927 --> 01:32:39,220
I could wave a flag, they said.
Nothing else.

1658
01:32:39,429 --> 01:32:43,140
So I wrote a legitimate drama,
very deep and very significant.

1659
01:32:43,350 --> 01:32:46,685
No music, no gags, no flag-waving.

1660
01:32:46,895 --> 01:32:48,646
I called it Popularity.

1661
01:32:48,855 --> 01:32:51,065
The title showed how hard I was hoping.

1662
01:32:51,733 --> 01:32:54,193
I couldn't attend the opening
because I was down the street...

1663
01:32:54,402 --> 01:32:56,028
...in The Yankee Prince.

1664
01:32:56,738 --> 01:32:58,822
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

1665
01:32:59,032 --> 01:33:01,242
MAN: Open it up.
GEORGE: Keep it closed, Buck.

1666
01:33:01,451 --> 01:33:03,702
Cohan, you're surely not going
to your dressing room now.

1667
01:33:03,912 --> 01:33:05,913
You're good for at least
another five curtain calls.

1668
01:33:06,122 --> 01:33:07,331
That's enough for tonight.

1669
01:33:07,541 --> 01:33:09,333
Mr. Cohan, are you sure you're feeling well?

1670
01:33:09,543 --> 01:33:11,835
I feel all right.
Any news from Popularity?

1671
01:33:12,045 --> 01:33:14,004
No, but they should be
ringing down just about now.

1672
01:33:14,214 --> 01:33:15,839
You'd think my family
would let me know.

1673
01:33:16,049 --> 01:33:19,009
Well, it's a good sign.
They probably couldn't tear themselves away.

1674
01:33:20,845 --> 01:33:22,137
- What time is it?
- Seven-thirty.

1675
01:33:22,347 --> 01:33:23,681
- That clock right?
- Yes, sir.

1676
01:33:23,890 --> 01:33:26,559
That's an early show.
They ought to be here by now.

1677
01:33:26,768 --> 01:33:30,062
- Maybe something wrong with Mom and Dad.
- I've got reports on the minstrel show.

1678
01:33:30,272 --> 01:33:32,690
- What'd we lose this week?
- Oh, 10,000, more or less.

1679
01:33:32,899 --> 01:33:35,484
- What's the total loss so far?
- A few dollars under 200,000.

1680
01:33:35,694 --> 01:33:38,112
Hmm.
That include the cost of the red ink?

1681
01:33:38,321 --> 01:33:40,948
Popularity better be a hit.
Got a lot of dough sunk in that too.

1682
01:33:41,157 --> 01:33:43,242
Eddie, call Wallachs and find out
what's keeping them.

1683
01:33:43,451 --> 01:33:45,244
What did the papers say
about the minstrel show?

1684
01:33:45,453 --> 01:33:47,621
Here they are.
Rave notices again.

1685
01:33:47,831 --> 01:33:49,540
Hmm, rave notices. That's bad.

1686
01:33:49,749 --> 01:33:52,376
The better notices you get on minstrel shows,
the more it costs you.

1687
01:33:52,586 --> 01:33:55,337
All except the last act.
Alecson suggests a new finish.

1688
01:33:55,547 --> 01:33:58,048
Hmm, I see. A new finish. Hm.

1689
01:33:58,258 --> 01:33:59,842
How about Saturday night?

1690
01:34:00,051 --> 01:34:01,969
- Close it?
- Close it.

1691
01:34:02,178 --> 01:34:03,887
- Saturday night.
- Mm-hm.

1692
01:34:04,097 --> 01:34:06,223
- Give the company two weeks' salary.
- All right.

1693
01:34:06,433 --> 01:34:08,726
- Oh, good evening, Mrs. Cohan.
JERRY: Good evening.

1694
01:34:08,935 --> 01:34:11,937
- Hello, dear.
GEORGE: Hello, Mom. Hi, darling.

1695
01:34:12,147 --> 01:34:14,231
Dad, I was worried about you.
I wondered what happened.

1696
01:34:14,441 --> 01:34:16,942
Sit down. Right here.
You sit down.

1697
01:34:17,152 --> 01:34:20,154
That theater's awfully cold, George.
Better have some more heat put in there.

1698
01:34:20,363 --> 01:34:22,990
- Take care of that right away.
- Remember that skating act in Camden?

1699
01:34:23,199 --> 01:34:25,284
They were there.
I wonder where they got the money.

1700
01:34:25,493 --> 01:34:27,328
Finnegan, Feeney, and Riley.
I remember them well.

1701
01:34:27,537 --> 01:34:29,246
Well, come on, tell me, how'd it go?

1702
01:34:29,456 --> 01:34:32,082
Well, the audience loved it,
every minute of it.

1703
01:34:32,626 --> 01:34:34,084
NELLIE:
The sets were beautiful, George.

1704
01:34:34,294 --> 01:34:35,794
Uh...

1705
01:34:40,258 --> 01:34:41,675
Why so quiet, Sam?

1706
01:34:41,885 --> 01:34:43,260
The toughest house I've ever seen.

1707
01:34:43,470 --> 01:34:46,138
The critics walked out at the end
of the second act.

1708
01:34:46,348 --> 01:34:47,598
GEORGE:
Hmm.

1709
01:34:49,309 --> 01:34:50,934
Mm-hm.

1710
01:34:51,394 --> 01:34:53,312
Come on, Dad. Come on, let's have it.

1711
01:34:53,521 --> 01:34:56,774
Heh. Well, there's no use
beating around the bush.

1712
01:34:56,983 --> 01:34:58,734
Pretty bad, George.

1713
01:34:58,943 --> 01:35:00,778
Could've been a lot better.

1714
01:35:01,237 --> 01:35:04,740
JERRY: All right, you write a bad play.
The only thing to do is forget about it.

1715
01:35:04,949 --> 01:35:06,992
Everybody's entitled to one failure.

1716
01:35:07,202 --> 01:35:10,329
Let's go to Delmonico's, have the party,
just as though the show was a hit.

1717
01:35:10,538 --> 01:35:13,624
You take the girls on over there,
and I'll see you in about a half-hour.

1718
01:35:13,833 --> 01:35:16,251
I've got some things I want
to talk over with Sam.

1719
01:35:23,093 --> 01:35:24,968
Those critics have been
after my blood for years.

1720
01:35:25,178 --> 01:35:28,138
They'll gang up on me and do a good job of it,
but I'll beat them to it.

1721
01:35:28,348 --> 01:35:30,808
I'll take an ad in every paper
right alongside their reviews...

1722
01:35:31,017 --> 01:35:33,519
...telling the public we've got
the greatest show in town...

1723
01:35:33,728 --> 01:35:36,063
...sold out for 10 weeks in advance,
we'll run a year.

1724
01:35:36,272 --> 01:35:38,148
The public will believe me.

1725
01:35:38,358 --> 01:35:40,109
- Listen, Georgie, you can't do that.
- Why not?

1726
01:35:40,318 --> 01:35:42,528
Too big a reputation.
You can't disappoint the public.

1727
01:35:42,737 --> 01:35:44,571
They'll never forgive you,
never trust you again.

1728
01:35:44,781 --> 01:35:47,157
We stuck our necks out,
and we got clipped.

1729
01:35:47,951 --> 01:35:49,326
Georgie.

1730
01:35:50,370 --> 01:35:52,121
You can't do this. You'll always regret it.

1731
01:35:52,330 --> 01:35:55,040
- Sit down and take this.
- We'll be sorry.

1732
01:35:55,250 --> 01:35:57,418
- To the theater-going public.
- George...

1733
01:35:57,627 --> 01:35:59,712
To the theater-going public.

1734
01:35:59,921 --> 01:36:02,506
I wrote a play called Popularity.

1735
01:36:02,716 --> 01:36:05,175
Mr. Harris and I produced that play.

1736
01:36:05,385 --> 01:36:08,178
In the opinion of people we respect,
it is a bad play.

1737
01:36:09,180 --> 01:36:11,014
In this, we heartily concur.

1738
01:36:11,224 --> 01:36:13,517
It is a very bad play.

1739
01:36:14,227 --> 01:36:16,186
I do humbly apologize
and ask forgiveness...

1740
01:36:16,396 --> 01:36:19,440
...for having presented anything
of which you couldn't possibly approve.

1741
01:36:19,649 --> 01:36:21,608
There will be five more performances.

1742
01:36:21,818 --> 01:36:23,402
Please miss them.

1743
01:36:23,611 --> 01:36:25,070
Signed...

1744
01:36:25,947 --> 01:36:27,281
Happy?

1745
01:36:29,117 --> 01:36:31,034
It's a wonderful second-act curtain.

1746
01:36:31,244 --> 01:36:33,454
Send copies of this to all the papers
for the next edition.

1747
01:36:33,663 --> 01:36:37,374
NEWSBOY:
Extra! Lusitania torpedoed by German sub!

1748
01:36:38,543 --> 01:36:40,502
[ALL SHOUTING]

1749
01:36:55,560 --> 01:36:57,019
This is it, George.

1750
01:36:57,228 --> 01:36:59,772
And we were worried about the success
or failure of a show.

1751
01:36:59,981 --> 01:37:02,274
Now we've really got something
to worry about.

1752
01:37:12,494 --> 01:37:13,786
GEORGE:
It seems it always happens.

1753
01:37:13,953 --> 01:37:17,080
Whenever we get too high-hat,
too sophisticated for flag-waving...

1754
01:37:17,290 --> 01:37:20,876
...some thug nation decides we're a pushover,
all ready to be blackjacked.

1755
01:37:21,085 --> 01:37:23,253
And it isn't long
before we're looking up anxiously...

1756
01:37:23,463 --> 01:37:25,631
...to be sure the flag's still waving over us.

1757
01:37:34,224 --> 01:37:36,183
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

1758
01:37:37,018 --> 01:37:38,477
MAN 1:
Left foot.

1759
01:37:38,686 --> 01:37:39,978
Right foot.

1760
01:37:40,188 --> 01:37:41,897
On your toes.

1761
01:37:42,899 --> 01:37:44,316
I used to be a model.

1762
01:37:44,526 --> 01:37:46,318
You'll look awful pretty
peeling potatoes.

1763
01:37:46,528 --> 01:37:49,029
- On your way, wise guy.
MAN 2: Next.

1764
01:37:49,989 --> 01:37:51,698
MAN 1:
Left foot. Right foot.

1765
01:37:51,908 --> 01:37:55,369
All right. Take this paper and report
to Sergeant Cooper for your examination.

1766
01:37:55,578 --> 01:37:57,996
Next. Name, please. Oh.

1767
01:37:58,206 --> 01:38:00,290
"George M. Cohan.

1768
01:38:00,500 --> 01:38:04,127
Occupation: actor, author,
composer, and producer.

1769
01:38:04,337 --> 01:38:07,923
- Address: Devonshire Hotel."
- How do you know so much about me?

1770
01:38:08,132 --> 01:38:11,927
Don't you recognize me, Mr. Cohan?
I used to be a clerk at the Friars Club.

1771
01:38:12,136 --> 01:38:14,930
- Oh.
- Heh-heh. "Age: 39."

1772
01:38:15,139 --> 01:38:18,725
- Doesn't even give me a chance to lie about it.
- Thirty-nine? I'm sorry, Mr. Cohan.

1773
01:38:18,935 --> 01:38:22,855
- You're overage. Thirty-one's the limit now.
- What's eight or nine years, more or less?

1774
01:38:23,064 --> 01:38:26,275
- The Germans won't ask for a birth certificate.
- I know how you feel, Mr. Cohan...

1775
01:38:26,484 --> 01:38:28,527
...but you've got to be young
and tough for this army.

1776
01:38:28,736 --> 01:38:30,529
It's no picnic, all those hardships.

1777
01:38:30,738 --> 01:38:33,532
The mental strain, the trenches,
the fighting, the marching.

1778
01:38:33,741 --> 01:38:35,534
MAN 2: And the mademoiselles.
- I hope.

1779
01:38:35,743 --> 01:38:39,246
- No, you'll never be able to stand it.
- Hardships and physical strain?

1780
01:38:39,455 --> 01:38:41,415
Young man, you don't know
what you're talking about.

1781
01:38:41,624 --> 01:38:44,293
This war's a coffee klatsch
compared to a season with a musical show.

1782
01:38:44,502 --> 01:38:46,044
I'd like to see
these kids do what I do...

1783
01:38:46,254 --> 01:38:48,338
...in a performance
and be on their feet at the finish.

1784
01:38:48,548 --> 01:38:50,173
I'll give you an idea of what I mean.

1785
01:39:01,311 --> 01:39:03,645
[ALL LAUGHING]

1786
01:39:03,855 --> 01:39:05,230
[MEN APPLAUDING]

1787
01:39:05,440 --> 01:39:07,816
Well, thank you very much
for your entertainment, Mr. Cohan...

1788
01:39:08,026 --> 01:39:10,652
...but I'm afraid we have more need
of you here than over there.

1789
01:39:10,862 --> 01:39:12,654
Well, that'll make the war
last a year longer.

1790
01:39:12,864 --> 01:39:13,822
[ALL LAUGH]

1791
01:39:14,032 --> 01:39:16,491
- Good-bye, Mr. Cohan.
- Thank you, major. Thank you.

1792
01:39:16,701 --> 01:39:18,452
MAN 3: So long.
MAN 4: Good-bye.

1793
01:39:19,203 --> 01:39:21,163
[BAND PLAYING MARCHING MUSIC]

1794
01:39:34,093 --> 01:39:35,886
[WHISTLING]

1795
01:39:47,190 --> 01:39:49,149
[PLAYING MEDLEY
FROM "OVER THERE" AND "TAPS"]

1796
01:40:21,891 --> 01:40:25,394
[SINGING] Johnny, get your gun
Get your gun, get your gun

1797
01:40:25,603 --> 01:40:28,981
Take it on the run
On the run, on the run

1798
01:40:29,190 --> 01:40:32,651
Hear them calling you and me

1799
01:40:32,860 --> 01:40:36,446
BOTH:
Every son of liberty

1800
01:40:36,656 --> 01:40:40,033
Hurry, right away! No delay. Go today.

1801
01:40:40,243 --> 01:40:43,704
NORA: Make your daddy glad
To have had such a lad

1802
01:40:43,913 --> 01:40:46,957
Tell your sweetheart not to pine

1803
01:40:47,166 --> 01:40:50,752
BOTH:
To be proud her boy's in line

1804
01:40:50,962 --> 01:40:54,297
Over there
Over there

1805
01:40:54,507 --> 01:40:57,968
Send the word, send the word
Over there

1806
01:40:58,177 --> 01:41:00,137
That the Yanks are coming

1807
01:41:00,346 --> 01:41:01,930
The Yanks are coming

1808
01:41:02,140 --> 01:41:05,350
The drums rum-tumming everywhere

1809
01:41:05,560 --> 01:41:08,687
So prepare
Say a prayer

1810
01:41:08,896 --> 01:41:12,691
Send the word, send the word
To beware

1811
01:41:12,900 --> 01:41:16,361
We'll be over
We're coming over

1812
01:41:16,571 --> 01:41:20,198
And we won't come back
Till it's over over there

1813
01:41:20,408 --> 01:41:22,034
Over there
Over there

1814
01:41:22,243 --> 01:41:23,702
[CROWD CHATTERING]

1815
01:41:23,911 --> 01:41:27,164
Send the word, send the word
Over there

1816
01:41:27,373 --> 01:41:30,000
GEORGE: Pick it up, soldier.
Keep singing, Nora.

1817
01:41:30,209 --> 01:41:32,836
MAN 1: Where are the lights?
MAN 2: The generator's gone again.

1818
01:41:33,046 --> 01:41:35,172
Hit your lights
so we can keep going, will ya?

1819
01:41:35,381 --> 01:41:36,840
- All right.
- Fine, thanks.

1820
01:41:37,050 --> 01:41:39,634
Hit your lights and keep them
on the singer until the others come.

1821
01:41:39,844 --> 01:41:41,428
- Certainly.
- Fine. Thanks very much.

1822
01:41:41,637 --> 01:41:44,181
CHORUS:
That the Yanks are coming

1823
01:41:44,390 --> 01:41:46,099
The Yanks are coming

1824
01:41:46,309 --> 01:41:49,436
The drums rum-tumming everywhere

1825
01:41:49,645 --> 01:41:53,065
So prepare
Say a prayer

1826
01:41:53,274 --> 01:41:56,902
Send the word, send the word
To beware

1827
01:41:57,111 --> 01:42:00,530
We'll be over
We're coming over

1828
01:42:00,740 --> 01:42:04,659
And we won't come back
Till it's over over there

1829
01:42:04,869 --> 01:42:06,536
Everybody sing!

1830
01:42:06,746 --> 01:42:10,624
ALL:
Over there

1831
01:42:10,833 --> 01:42:13,043
Over there

1832
01:42:13,252 --> 01:42:17,047
Send the word, send the word
Over there

1833
01:42:17,256 --> 01:42:19,633
That the Yanks are coming

1834
01:42:19,842 --> 01:42:21,802
The Yanks are coming

1835
01:42:22,011 --> 01:42:25,889
The drums rum-tumming everywhere

1836
01:42:26,099 --> 01:42:28,016
So prepare

1837
01:42:28,226 --> 01:42:30,185
Say a prayer

1838
01:42:30,394 --> 01:42:34,272
Send the word, send the word
To beware

1839
01:42:34,482 --> 01:42:36,608
We'll be over

1840
01:42:36,818 --> 01:42:38,944
We're coming over

1841
01:42:39,153 --> 01:42:43,448
And we won't come back
Till it's over over there

1842
01:42:43,658 --> 01:42:45,617
[MUSIC ENDS
AND ALL CHEER WILDLY]

1843
01:42:58,131 --> 01:43:00,090
[HORN BLOWING]

1844
01:43:13,521 --> 01:43:14,688
GEORGE:
We'd won the World War.

1845
01:43:14,897 --> 01:43:17,149
Manhattan went wild
with postwar hysteria.

1846
01:43:17,358 --> 01:43:19,192
But I spiked my shows
with prewar stuff...

1847
01:43:19,402 --> 01:43:22,154
...the sentiment and humor an older America
had aged in the wood.

1848
01:43:22,363 --> 01:43:24,948
WOMAN [SINGING]:
In a kingdom all our own

1849
01:43:25,158 --> 01:43:27,993
With little cupid on the throne

1850
01:43:28,202 --> 01:43:31,621
With a prince
And princess on my knee

1851
01:43:31,831 --> 01:43:34,624
You'll be as happy as can be

1852
01:43:34,834 --> 01:43:37,836
In a love nest

1853
01:43:38,045 --> 01:43:41,047
Cozy and warm

1854
01:43:41,257 --> 01:43:44,217
Like a dove nest

1855
01:43:44,427 --> 01:43:47,387
Down on a farm

1856
01:43:47,597 --> 01:43:51,057
And it's all day long

1857
01:43:51,267 --> 01:43:52,475
They bray

1858
01:43:52,685 --> 01:43:55,520
Flowers all dripping with dew

1859
01:43:55,730 --> 01:43:59,858
And they join in the chorus
Of Nellie Kelly

1860
01:44:00,067 --> 01:44:03,987
I love you

1861
01:44:04,197 --> 01:44:07,407
He is the man
Who owns Broadway

1862
01:44:07,617 --> 01:44:10,577
That's what the daily papers say

1863
01:44:10,786 --> 01:44:13,163
Oh, where could you find another?

1864
01:44:13,372 --> 01:44:15,165
I'd like to be shown

1865
01:44:15,374 --> 01:44:19,586
Another like Molly Malone

1866
01:44:19,795 --> 01:44:24,299
But I love the name Billie

1867
01:44:24,508 --> 01:44:26,676
My dad's was the same

1868
01:44:26,886 --> 01:44:29,304
Billie

1869
01:44:41,275 --> 01:44:43,944
GEORGE:
Still, it was lonely on the main stem.

1870
01:44:44,153 --> 01:44:45,904
Mother and Josie were gone.

1871
01:44:46,113 --> 01:44:48,823
Dad was by himself on the farm
and had grown very old.

1872
01:44:49,033 --> 01:44:51,993
Every night I went to the theater,
I expected a phone call.

1873
01:44:52,203 --> 01:44:54,537
Well, finally it came.

1874
01:45:03,631 --> 01:45:06,258
You'd better give him two more ccs.

1875
01:45:06,467 --> 01:45:08,843
We might as well try to make him
as comfortable as possible.

1876
01:45:09,053 --> 01:45:11,221
Yes, Dr. Anderson.

1877
01:45:11,430 --> 01:45:15,642
If you have to get back to town,
Dr. Llewellyn, I'll be here all night.

1878
01:45:15,851 --> 01:45:18,937
It's all right. I'll wait till George M. gets here
from the theater.

1879
01:45:19,146 --> 01:45:21,982
- Cigarette, doctor?
- Yes, I will.

1880
01:45:22,817 --> 01:45:24,067
Thanks.

1881
01:45:24,277 --> 01:45:26,820
I remember I was a kid
in medical college in Baltimore...

1882
01:45:27,029 --> 01:45:29,197
...when I first saw The Four Cohans.

1883
01:45:29,824 --> 01:45:31,491
They were a great act.

1884
01:45:31,951 --> 01:45:33,451
Yes, they were.

1885
01:45:36,497 --> 01:45:40,875
I always thought George M.'s sister
was the loveliest dancer I'd ever seen.

1886
01:45:41,085 --> 01:45:44,754
Can't help thinking a theatrical era
is dying in there.

1887
01:45:45,172 --> 01:45:48,383
His sister and his mother gone
and now the old man.

1888
01:45:48,592 --> 01:45:51,594
In some ways, I think he was
the best performer of the lot.

1889
01:45:51,804 --> 01:45:54,597
Well, I'd settle for his age.

1890
01:45:54,807 --> 01:45:57,600
There never was anything dull
about his life, either.

1891
01:45:57,810 --> 01:46:00,353
And he's lived to see his son
an American institution.

1892
01:46:00,563 --> 01:46:01,980
Yeah.

1893
01:46:02,189 --> 01:46:03,732
I'd settle for that too.

1894
01:46:09,697 --> 01:46:11,239
DOCTOR:
Hello, Mr. Cohan.

1895
01:46:11,449 --> 01:46:13,074
- How is he?
- Resting quietly.

1896
01:46:13,284 --> 01:46:15,285
Oh. I see.

1897
01:46:17,330 --> 01:46:19,331
I think you'd better go in alone.

1898
01:46:24,587 --> 01:46:27,088
We can't... We can't do that.

1899
01:46:27,298 --> 01:46:29,299
Wait till George gets here.
Where's George?

1900
01:46:29,508 --> 01:46:31,468
Here I am, Dad. Here I am.

1901
01:46:32,053 --> 01:46:35,263
Oh, that's good. I'm glad you came.

1902
01:46:36,015 --> 01:46:38,558
The booking office
has been calling up all day...

1903
01:46:38,768 --> 01:46:41,644
...and they want us to play Des Moines
the last half of the week.

1904
01:46:41,854 --> 01:46:44,856
Don't worry about that. We're not going to.
I've canceled it.

1905
01:46:45,066 --> 01:46:47,192
We can pick it up on the way back.

1906
01:46:48,486 --> 01:46:52,364
- How did it go tonight? Mmm.
- Oh, fine. Fine. Yeah.

1907
01:46:52,573 --> 01:46:56,201
It's not every kid gets that gets
the chance to play Peck's bad boy.

1908
01:46:56,410 --> 01:46:57,827
That's right.

1909
01:46:58,037 --> 01:47:01,915
Were you? Were you nervous?
Did you remember your lines?

1910
01:47:02,124 --> 01:47:03,666
Oh, sure. Every one.

1911
01:47:03,876 --> 01:47:06,503
- "I can lick any kid in town."
- Heh. Good.

1912
01:47:07,963 --> 01:47:11,716
Now, don't you upstage your mother,
or I'll whale the tar out of you.

1913
01:47:12,134 --> 01:47:14,719
Don't worry, Dad. I'll never do that.

1914
01:47:14,929 --> 01:47:17,013
I'll play the whole show
with one foot in the trough.

1915
01:47:17,223 --> 01:47:20,100
No, no, no.
We've been billed as The Four Cohans.

1916
01:47:20,351 --> 01:47:22,060
You're not gonna break up the act.

1917
01:47:22,269 --> 01:47:23,728
Don't worry, Dad. They never will.

1918
01:47:23,938 --> 01:47:26,398
We won't let them. Won't let them.

1919
01:47:27,525 --> 01:47:29,484
JERRY: How many curtain calls
did you take tonight?

1920
01:47:29,693 --> 01:47:31,528
GEORGE:
Six. Six curtains.

1921
01:47:31,737 --> 01:47:34,447
- That's pretty good for a drama.
- Yeah.

1922
01:47:36,033 --> 01:47:40,120
- Did you make a speech?
- Mm-hm. I thanked them for us.

1923
01:47:41,414 --> 01:47:43,415
I said, "My mother thanks you...

1924
01:47:43,624 --> 01:47:45,959
...my father thanks you...

1925
01:47:46,168 --> 01:47:48,294
...my sister thanks you...

1926
01:47:49,296 --> 01:47:51,464
[SOBBING]
...and I thank you.

1927
01:48:57,990 --> 01:48:59,532
GEORGE:
Well...

1928
01:49:01,702 --> 01:49:05,121
...it was a good combination, Sam,
worked well for a long time.

1929
01:49:05,331 --> 01:49:07,916
Yeah, now that it's all over,
who was the senior partner...

1930
01:49:08,125 --> 01:49:09,459
...and who was the junior partner?

1931
01:49:09,668 --> 01:49:11,461
You mean, who was Dietz
and who was Goff?

1932
01:49:11,670 --> 01:49:15,757
Well, I bet it's the first firm in the history
of show business had two senior partners.

1933
01:49:15,966 --> 01:49:18,092
Well, uh, you know how I feel,
don't you, Sam?

1934
01:49:18,302 --> 01:49:20,136
Sure. I understand.

1935
01:49:20,346 --> 01:49:23,431
You know, when Dad died, with him went
the last link with The Four Cohans.

1936
01:49:23,641 --> 01:49:27,393
All the backslapping and the applause,
well, it became unimportant.

1937
01:49:27,603 --> 01:49:29,145
No more fun in it.

1938
01:49:29,355 --> 01:49:32,357
It didn't mean anything anymore
with Dad, Mom and Josie gone.

1939
01:49:33,526 --> 01:49:36,236
So Mary and I are going away
and enjoy ourselves...

1940
01:49:36,445 --> 01:49:38,363
...and visit places
we've always wanted to see...

1941
01:49:38,572 --> 01:49:41,741
...old theaters
where nobody ever even heard of us.

1942
01:49:41,951 --> 01:49:43,451
You'll have to go to Timbuktu.

1943
01:49:44,203 --> 01:49:45,161
We've got it booked.

1944
01:49:45,371 --> 01:49:48,456
George, you've always been
the one with the words.

1945
01:49:48,666 --> 01:49:51,334
I never was much of a hand
at saying things.

1946
01:49:52,127 --> 01:49:54,963
But we've done more
than make a lot of money...

1947
01:49:55,839 --> 01:49:57,298
...and lose a little.

1948
01:49:58,050 --> 01:50:01,511
Sometimes friends drift apart.
Let's not let that happen to us.

1949
01:50:02,429 --> 01:50:05,098
No matter how legal the dissolution
of this partnership is, Sam...

1950
01:50:05,307 --> 01:50:07,600
...50 percent of me will always be here
in this office.

1951
01:50:07,810 --> 01:50:09,727
I'll remember that
when the rent comes due.

1952
01:50:09,937 --> 01:50:11,396
You'll be more successful than ever.

1953
01:50:11,605 --> 01:50:15,066
But if ever the rent does come due
and you can't meet it, well, you know...

1954
01:50:15,276 --> 01:50:17,735
...and by the same token,
if I get stuck in Madagascar...

1955
01:50:17,945 --> 01:50:19,487
Heh-heh.
-- you'll hear from me.

1956
01:50:21,657 --> 01:50:23,408
You'd better get out of here.

1957
01:50:25,786 --> 01:50:27,996
That ship will sail without you.

1958
01:50:34,837 --> 01:50:36,754
- Seasick pills.
- Mm-hm.

1959
01:50:36,964 --> 01:50:38,756
SAM:
I won't go to the boat with you.

1960
01:50:38,966 --> 01:50:40,675
You know how red my nose gets.

1961
01:50:43,429 --> 01:50:45,972
What's this? We thought you guys
weren't speaking to each other.

1962
01:50:46,181 --> 01:50:48,766
Can we have a picture
of you tearing up your contract?

1963
01:50:48,976 --> 01:50:51,644
That's impossible.
We never had a written contract.

1964
01:50:52,605 --> 01:50:54,230
The only contract we've ever had.

1965
01:50:54,440 --> 01:50:56,691
Hold that pose. We want to show it
to our legal department.

1966
01:50:56,900 --> 01:50:58,067
Shoot it, boys.

1967
01:51:00,487 --> 01:51:02,447
[HORN BLOWING]

1968
01:51:03,657 --> 01:51:06,326
GEORGE: Life was less full,
but it was by no means empty.

1969
01:51:06,535 --> 01:51:09,746
I still had Mary,
a playmate as well as a helpmate.

1970
01:51:09,955 --> 01:51:12,165
We set out to rubberneck at the world.

1971
01:51:18,297 --> 01:51:20,840
Nelson monument. It's a good thing
I wasn't born an Englishman.

1972
01:51:21,050 --> 01:51:23,593
With the history their flag has,
I'd have waved myself to death.

1973
01:51:24,303 --> 01:51:26,262
[GEORGE YODELING]

1974
01:51:27,514 --> 01:51:29,682
Oh, George,
I didn't know you could yodel.

1975
01:51:29,892 --> 01:51:33,227
Learned it on the farm.
Nothing but hog-calling with frost on it.

1976
01:51:42,488 --> 01:51:44,656
It takes two men to impersonate
a horse on Broadway.

1977
01:51:44,865 --> 01:51:47,408
And you always have trouble
casting the front end.

1978
01:51:53,540 --> 01:51:55,958
GEORGE: But folks always come back
to where their heart is...

1979
01:51:56,168 --> 01:51:57,627
...so we came back to the farm...

1980
01:51:57,836 --> 01:52:01,214
...the farm we Cohans had dreamed of
when farmers were envying us.

1981
01:52:04,176 --> 01:52:06,135
[CAR ENGINE RATTLING]

1982
01:52:09,890 --> 01:52:11,849
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1983
01:52:13,060 --> 01:52:16,854
Hey, mister, our radiator needs some H2O.
Can we use your well?

1984
01:52:17,731 --> 01:52:19,816
Sure, go ahead. Help yourselves.

1985
01:52:20,025 --> 01:52:22,360
Come on, Jack.
Let's make this hop-up solid.

1986
01:52:22,569 --> 01:52:25,988
Okay, Jackson, come on.
This isn't any free jitney.

1987
01:52:26,615 --> 01:52:27,615
GEORGE:
Radiator busted?

1988
01:52:27,825 --> 01:52:29,867
Nah. It's only got high blood pressure.

1989
01:52:30,077 --> 01:52:31,994
What are you gonna do about tires
if those give out?

1990
01:52:32,204 --> 01:52:34,122
Oh, it'll run a lot smoother on the rims.

1991
01:52:34,331 --> 01:52:36,499
"Stix nix hix pix."

1992
01:52:37,251 --> 01:52:39,168
Greek. I'll bet that's Greek talk.

1993
01:52:39,378 --> 01:52:42,088
BOY: That ain't Greek.
That's Swedish or Russian. Stix nix hix pix.

1994
01:52:42,297 --> 01:52:44,674
That's show business talk.
Here, I'll translate it for you.

1995
01:52:44,883 --> 01:52:49,053
"Stix," small towns, "nix," refuse,
"hix," rube, "pix," pictures.

1996
01:52:49,263 --> 01:52:51,848
"Small towns refuse rube pictures."
Stix nix hix pix.

1997
01:52:52,057 --> 01:52:53,683
- Stix nix hix pix.
- Stix nix hix pix.

1998
01:52:53,934 --> 01:52:56,436
BOTH [SINGING]:
A-stix a-nix hix a-pix

1999
01:52:56,645 --> 01:52:58,229
A-stix a-nix hix pix

2000
01:52:58,439 --> 01:53:00,648
- I thought that was new jive talk.
- New what talk?

2001
01:53:00,858 --> 01:53:02,400
- Jive talk.
- Oh.

2002
01:53:02,609 --> 01:53:04,402
- Are you an actor, sir?
GEORGE: Used to be.

2003
01:53:04,611 --> 01:53:06,571
- What were some of your pictures?
- Not in pictures.

2004
01:53:06,780 --> 01:53:08,573
I was on Broadway
in the legitimate theater.

2005
01:53:08,782 --> 01:53:10,825
Oh. What's your name, sir?

2006
01:53:11,034 --> 01:53:12,368
- Cohan.
- Cohen?

2007
01:53:12,578 --> 01:53:14,328
Cohan. George M. Cohan.

2008
01:53:14,538 --> 01:53:17,206
BOY: You must have been before our time.
- Yes, guess I was.

2009
01:53:17,416 --> 01:53:18,875
Were you ever in some big shows?

2010
01:53:19,084 --> 01:53:20,501
- Yeah, a few.
- Like what?

2011
01:53:20,711 --> 01:53:23,337
Oh, uh, like, uh, Little Nellie Kelly.

2012
01:53:23,547 --> 01:53:25,465
- The Tavern. Ah, Wilderness!
- Uh-uh.

2013
01:53:25,674 --> 01:53:27,717
Mmm. Raised in a vacuum bottle.

2014
01:53:27,926 --> 01:53:30,803
Well, I guess your parents must have seen me,
uh, fathers and mothers.

2015
01:53:31,013 --> 01:53:33,222
BOY: Maybe they have.
I never heard them talk about it.

2016
01:53:33,432 --> 01:53:36,100
Have you ever heard a song called, uh,
"Give My Regards to Broadway"?

2017
01:53:36,310 --> 01:53:38,770
- I don't think so.
- Mmm. No, sir. Who sang it?

2018
01:53:39,480 --> 01:53:41,939
- Who sang it?
GIRL: Oh, was it a theme song or something?

2019
01:53:42,149 --> 01:53:45,902
- Did that follow "Beat Me Daddy, 8 to the Bar"?
- Yes! Or "Jeepers Creepers."

2020
01:53:46,111 --> 01:53:48,279
ALL [SINGING]:
Jeepers creepers

2021
01:53:48,489 --> 01:53:50,448
Where'd you get those peepers?

2022
01:53:50,657 --> 01:53:52,950
Jeepers creepers

2023
01:53:53,160 --> 01:53:54,619
Where'd you get those eyes?

2024
01:53:54,828 --> 01:53:56,204
Come on, kids. Time's a-wasting.

2025
01:53:56,413 --> 01:53:58,289
Well, we gotta scram now.
Swinging session.

2026
01:53:58,499 --> 01:54:00,583
Thank you very much, mister...
What was your name again?

2027
01:54:00,793 --> 01:54:02,919
Cohan. George Cohan.

2028
01:54:03,796 --> 01:54:05,087
Good-bye, Georgie.

2029
01:54:05,297 --> 01:54:06,672
You're cute!

2030
01:54:07,257 --> 01:54:09,759
BOY: Nice old guy.
We gotta get to that session, let's go.

2031
01:54:09,968 --> 01:54:12,428
Come on, we got places to go
and things to do.

2032
01:54:12,638 --> 01:54:14,013
[ENGINE STARTS]

2033
01:54:14,223 --> 01:54:15,681
GIRLS:
Bye!

2034
01:54:20,854 --> 01:54:22,480
They did that.

2035
01:54:23,106 --> 01:54:24,982
I'm not angry,
but it is very discouraging.

2036
01:54:25,192 --> 01:54:28,486
Kid asked me my name, and I said Cohan.
He asked me again, and I said Cohan.

2037
01:54:28,695 --> 01:54:31,823
Hm. Never even heard of me.
Sixteen years old, and I bet you he can't read.

2038
01:54:32,032 --> 01:54:34,617
But you've been away from that theater
for years, George. Years.

2039
01:54:34,827 --> 01:54:36,953
Nine or 10 generations
have grown up since then.

2040
01:54:37,162 --> 01:54:40,081
Naturally, they don't remember you.
Nobody's got that good a memory.

2041
01:54:40,290 --> 01:54:43,501
Why not? Many generations remembered
my father and mother in vaudeville.

2042
01:54:43,710 --> 01:54:46,879
That's because they were real troupers.
They stayed with it.

2043
01:54:47,089 --> 01:54:49,465
Your father could do a buck-and-wing
when he was 60 years old.

2044
01:54:49,675 --> 01:54:52,426
- What makes you think I can't?
- I'd hate to see you try it.

2045
01:54:52,636 --> 01:54:55,805
Your father never sat around an orchard
listening to his arteries hardening.

2046
01:54:56,014 --> 01:54:58,349
- Nothing the matter with my arteries.
- No, not right now...

2047
01:54:58,559 --> 01:55:01,352
...because those kids got you all worked up.

2048
01:55:01,562 --> 01:55:03,479
You're picking on me for a reason, Mary.

2049
01:55:03,689 --> 01:55:06,524
You're trying to get a rise out of me.
Come on, let's have it. What is it?

2050
01:55:07,359 --> 01:55:09,193
All right. Here it is.

2051
01:55:10,028 --> 01:55:12,697
I got a long-distance call
from Sam Harris this afternoon.

2052
01:55:12,906 --> 01:55:14,156
What about?

2053
01:55:14,366 --> 01:55:16,784
He's producing a new show
by Kaufman and Hart.

2054
01:55:16,952 --> 01:55:19,412
They're good writers.
Nothing I could do to improve their stuff.

2055
01:55:20,122 --> 01:55:22,456
Sam thinks you could,
if you played the lead.

2056
01:55:23,625 --> 01:55:26,168
Play the lead?
Now, what is the matter with that man?

2057
01:55:26,378 --> 01:55:29,630
Hasn't he got any sense at all?
What's he trying to do, spoil our fun?

2058
01:55:29,840 --> 01:55:31,841
But are you having fun, George?

2059
01:55:32,050 --> 01:55:34,302
When we were in Europe,
you haunted every theater...

2060
01:55:34,511 --> 01:55:36,679
...not knowing a word
that was said onstage.

2061
01:55:36,889 --> 01:55:38,598
Going back, congratulating the actors...

2062
01:55:38,807 --> 01:55:40,933
They didn't even know
what you were talking about.

2063
01:55:41,143 --> 01:55:42,894
-- just to smell that greasepaint again.

2064
01:55:43,103 --> 01:55:44,437
You think I'm stagestruck.

2065
01:55:44,646 --> 01:55:47,565
The only reason I ever go near a theater
is to get out of the night air.

2066
01:55:47,774 --> 01:55:49,859
Fun? I'm having a wonderful time.

2067
01:55:50,068 --> 01:55:52,153
I have nothing to do with Broadway.

2068
01:55:52,779 --> 01:55:56,240
Sam says it's a great part, no other actor
in the world but you could do it.

2069
01:55:56,450 --> 01:55:58,284
That's just some more of that Harris con.

2070
01:55:58,493 --> 01:56:00,912
He needs me about as much
as he needs a hole in the head.

2071
01:56:01,121 --> 01:56:03,539
He really does need you, George.
He's in trouble.

2072
01:56:03,749 --> 01:56:07,627
If positions were reversed, he'd help you out.
You know he would.

2073
01:56:08,337 --> 01:56:10,880
Besides, he never said so,
but Sam's broke.

2074
01:56:12,257 --> 01:56:14,008
Can you think of any more reasons?

2075
01:56:16,219 --> 01:56:18,179
Yes. I want you to.

2076
01:56:18,931 --> 01:56:21,599
Well, that settled it.

2077
01:56:21,808 --> 01:56:23,601
I've never refused you anything, have I?

2078
01:56:23,810 --> 01:56:25,937
We do it. Come on, let's get packing.

2079
01:56:26,146 --> 01:56:27,813
We're all packed.

2080
01:56:28,899 --> 01:56:29,857
What?

2081
01:56:30,943 --> 01:56:32,818
We're all packed, dear.

2082
01:56:33,612 --> 01:56:35,780
Now you can start getting mad
all over again...

2083
01:56:35,989 --> 01:56:38,950
...because I told Sam
I'd talk you into it.

2084
01:56:39,159 --> 01:56:41,077
[GEORGE LAUGHING]

2085
01:56:43,538 --> 01:56:45,957
What are you laughing about?

2086
01:56:46,166 --> 01:56:49,335
Just full of news, aren't you?
Telling me all kinds of things, huh?

2087
01:56:49,544 --> 01:56:51,379
Well, I want you to know
I knew it all the time.

2088
01:56:51,588 --> 01:56:55,257
I was listening in on the phone downstairs
while you were talking to Sam.

2089
01:56:55,467 --> 01:56:58,260
Why, you devil.
You knew it all the time!

2090
01:56:58,470 --> 01:57:01,347
And what's more, I phoned Sam right back
and told him I'd play it.

2091
01:57:01,556 --> 01:57:03,307
Oh, I ought to pop you.

2092
01:57:03,517 --> 01:57:05,935
- You... You...
- Heh-heh-heh. Oh!

2093
01:57:06,144 --> 01:57:07,979
- Oh.
- Oh.

2094
01:57:08,605 --> 01:57:10,064
[GEORGE LAUGHING]

2095
01:57:11,024 --> 01:57:12,984
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING UPBEAT PLAYING]

2096
01:57:15,654 --> 01:57:17,613
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

2097
01:57:26,665 --> 01:57:28,791
[SINGING]
It's really a wonderful job

2098
01:57:29,793 --> 01:57:32,712
For fellows like George, Abe and me too

2099
01:57:32,921 --> 01:57:35,631
It's great to shake hands with a mob

2100
01:57:35,841 --> 01:57:38,843
And to hold every kid on your knee too

2101
01:57:39,052 --> 01:57:42,138
Every word that I speak
Goes into headlines

2102
01:57:42,347 --> 01:57:45,141
When I speak
All the papers hold their deadlines

2103
01:57:45,350 --> 01:57:47,727
But I have found a way
Of dropping a hint

2104
01:57:47,936 --> 01:57:51,814
Or a glint of the truth
That the boys cannot print

2105
01:57:52,024 --> 01:57:53,399
For instance

2106
01:57:53,608 --> 01:57:55,151
For instance

2107
01:57:58,363 --> 01:57:59,864
When I was courting Eleanor

2108
01:58:00,073 --> 01:58:02,742
I told her Uncle Teddy
I wouldn't run for president

2109
01:58:02,951 --> 01:58:04,493
Unless the job was steady

2110
01:58:04,703 --> 01:58:07,121
Don't print it
Strictly off the record

2111
01:58:07,789 --> 01:58:10,833
We entertained the royalty
But we were never flustered

2112
01:58:11,043 --> 01:58:14,045
We gave them Yankee hot dogs
With Colman's English Mustard

2113
01:58:14,254 --> 01:58:16,547
Don't print it
Strictly off the record

2114
01:58:17,299 --> 01:58:20,176
It's pleasant at the White House
But I'll tell you how I feel

2115
01:58:20,385 --> 01:58:23,345
The food is simply terrible
Just sauerkraut and veal

2116
01:58:23,555 --> 01:58:26,515
If Mrs. R. would stay at home
I'd get a decent meal

2117
01:58:26,725 --> 01:58:29,143
But that's off the record

2118
01:59:08,058 --> 01:59:09,433
When I go up to Hyde Park

2119
01:59:09,643 --> 01:59:11,102
It's not for just the ride there

2120
01:59:11,311 --> 01:59:12,645
It's not that I like Hyde Park

2121
01:59:12,854 --> 01:59:14,438
But I love to park and hide there

2122
01:59:14,648 --> 01:59:16,398
Don't print it
It's strictly off the record

2123
01:59:17,651 --> 01:59:20,569
I sit up in my study
Writing gags for Mr. Ickes

2124
01:59:20,779 --> 01:59:22,196
And insults for the gentlemen

2125
01:59:22,405 --> 01:59:23,864
Who'd love to slip him Mickeys

2126
01:59:24,074 --> 01:59:26,492
Don't print that
Off the record

2127
01:59:42,801 --> 01:59:45,886
I scrapped the Prohibition Act
When we required a bracer

2128
01:59:46,096 --> 01:59:49,181
And finished up the Boulder Dam
To give the boys a chaser

2129
01:59:49,391 --> 01:59:52,184
Don't print it
It's strictly off the record

2130
01:59:52,394 --> 01:59:55,396
And for my friends in Washington
Who complain about the taxes

2131
01:59:55,605 --> 01:59:58,649
Who cares as long as we can knock
The ax out of the Axis?

2132
01:59:58,859 --> 02:00:01,694
Don't print it
It's strictly off the record

2133
02:00:01,903 --> 02:00:04,947
I can't forget how Lafayette
Helped give us our first chance

2134
02:00:05,157 --> 02:00:08,033
To win our fight for liberty
And now they've taken France

2135
02:00:08,243 --> 02:00:11,120
We'll take it back from Hitler
And put ants in his Ja-pants

2136
02:00:11,329 --> 02:00:13,873
And that's for the record

2137
02:00:14,082 --> 02:00:16,041
[AUDIENCE CHEERING AND APPLAUDING]

2138
02:00:29,681 --> 02:00:32,474
Good work, kids.
I'll see you at 11 in the morning.

2139
02:00:35,437 --> 02:00:38,189
And then came your wire,
and I was really worried.

2140
02:00:38,899 --> 02:00:41,942
Well, here I am going on like Tennyson's book,
giving you the story of my life.

2141
02:00:42,152 --> 02:00:44,069
I'm sorry. You should've stopped me.

2142
02:00:44,279 --> 02:00:46,739
Why, I wanted to hear
the story of your life.

2143
02:00:46,948 --> 02:00:50,326
It has a direct bearing
on my sending for you.

2144
02:00:50,535 --> 02:00:52,494
Do you know what this is?

2145
02:00:54,164 --> 02:00:55,497
The Congressional Medal of Honor.

2146
02:00:55,707 --> 02:00:57,666
Let's see what the inscription says.

2147
02:00:58,585 --> 02:01:00,544
PRESIDENT [READING INSCRIPTION]:

2148
02:01:10,889 --> 02:01:13,140
I congratulate you, Mr. Cohan.

2149
02:01:13,350 --> 02:01:17,603
I understand you're the first person
of your profession to receive this honor.

2150
02:01:17,812 --> 02:01:19,855
You should be very proud.

2151
02:01:20,065 --> 02:01:21,565
Oh, I am proud.

2152
02:01:21,775 --> 02:01:23,317
In fact, I'm flabbergasted.

2153
02:01:23,526 --> 02:01:25,569
First time in my life,
I'm speechless.

2154
02:01:25,779 --> 02:01:28,322
Uh... You're sure there
isn't some mistake?

2155
02:01:28,531 --> 02:01:30,241
Quite sure.

2156
02:01:31,618 --> 02:01:35,162
This medal is for people who've given their lives
for their country or done something big.

2157
02:01:35,372 --> 02:01:37,748
I'm just a song-and-dance man.
Everybody knows that.

2158
02:01:37,958 --> 02:01:42,753
A man may give his life to his country
in many different ways, Mr. Cohan.

2159
02:01:42,963 --> 02:01:47,174
And quite often, he isn't the best judge
of how much he has given.

2160
02:01:47,384 --> 02:01:50,844
Your songs were a symbol
of the American spirit.

2161
02:01:51,054 --> 02:01:54,890
"Over There" was just as powerful
a weapon as any cannon...

2162
02:01:55,100 --> 02:01:58,519
...as any battleship we had
in the first World War.

2163
02:01:58,728 --> 02:02:02,147
Today, we're all soldiers.
We're all on the front.

2164
02:02:02,357 --> 02:02:05,276
We need more songs to express America.

2165
02:02:05,485 --> 02:02:09,154
I know you and your comrades
will give them to us.

2166
02:02:09,364 --> 02:02:13,242
Mr. President, I've just begun
to earn this medal.

2167
02:02:13,451 --> 02:02:14,868
It's quite a thing.

2168
02:02:15,078 --> 02:02:20,124
Well, it's the best material we could find,
what with priorities and all.

2169
02:02:21,626 --> 02:02:23,335
Good-bye, sir.

2170
02:02:23,962 --> 02:02:27,423
And I want you to know
that I'm not the only one that's grateful.

2171
02:02:27,632 --> 02:02:29,550
My mother thanks you,
my father thanks you...

2172
02:02:29,759 --> 02:02:32,928
...my sister thanks you,
and I assure you, I thank you.

2173
02:02:33,138 --> 02:02:36,640
And, uh, I wouldn't worry
about this country if I were you.

2174
02:02:36,850 --> 02:02:38,475
We've got this thing licked.

2175
02:02:38,685 --> 02:02:42,479
Where else could a plain guy like me come in
and talk things over with the head man?

2176
02:02:42,689 --> 02:02:44,982
Well, that's about as good
a definition of America...

2177
02:02:45,191 --> 02:02:46,859
...as any I've ever heard.

2178
02:02:47,068 --> 02:02:49,320
Good-bye, Mr. Cohan, and good luck.

2179
02:02:49,529 --> 02:02:51,780
Good-bye, sir, and good luck to you.

2180
02:03:28,610 --> 02:03:30,569
[CROWD CHEERING OUTSIDE]

2181
02:03:35,075 --> 02:03:36,992
[MARCHING BAND PLAYING
"OVER THERE"]

2182
02:03:51,049 --> 02:03:52,758
CROWD [SINGING]:
Over there

2183
02:03:52,967 --> 02:03:54,843
Over there

2184
02:03:55,053 --> 02:03:58,847
Send the word, send the word
Over there

2185
02:03:59,057 --> 02:04:01,141
That the Yanks are coming

2186
02:04:01,393 --> 02:04:03,060
The Yanks are coming

2187
02:04:03,269 --> 02:04:06,688
The drums rum-tumming everywhere

2188
02:04:06,898 --> 02:04:10,943
So prepare
Say a prayer

2189
02:04:11,152 --> 02:04:14,905
Send the word, send the word
To beware

2190
02:04:15,115 --> 02:04:16,698
We'll be over

2191
02:04:16,908 --> 02:04:18,909
We're coming over

2192
02:04:19,077 --> 02:04:21,703
And we won't come back
Till it's over

2193
02:04:21,913 --> 02:04:24,665
What's the matter, old-timer?
Don't you remember this song?

2194
02:04:24,874 --> 02:04:26,583
Seems to me I do.

2195
02:04:26,793 --> 02:04:28,419
Well, I don't hear anything.

2196
02:04:28,628 --> 02:04:30,879
Send the word over there

2197
02:04:31,089 --> 02:04:33,215
That the Yanks are coming

2198
02:04:33,425 --> 02:04:34,883
The Yanks are coming

2199
02:04:35,093 --> 02:04:38,887
The drums rum-tumming everywhere

2200
02:04:39,097 --> 02:04:42,933
So prepare
Say a prayer

2201
02:04:43,143 --> 02:04:46,937
Send the word, send the word
To beware

2202
02:04:47,147 --> 02:04:50,941
We'll be over
We're coming over

2203
02:04:51,151 --> 02:04:55,362
And we won't come back
Till it's over over there


